 I am very happy to speak here before you about St. Augustine and Orthodox Theology and Piety.

21
00:02:47,000 --> 00:02:54,000
 Before we begin to consider the reception of Augustine in Orthodox Theology and Piety,

22
00:02:54,000 --> 00:03:00,000
 it is important to outline what actually Orthodoxy is.

23
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:07,000
 It is very important because it helps to better understand specifics that simply need to be taken into account

24
00:03:07,000 --> 00:03:13,000
 before starting to consider one or another theological issue.

25
00:03:13,000 --> 00:03:21,000
 In their theological discourse, representatives of the Orthodox tradition talk about Orthodoxy.

26
00:03:21,000 --> 00:03:30,000
 Typically, they mean two things at the same time, but normally this is not indicated.

27
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:40,000
 Firstly, by Orthodoxy we mean the entire ancient theological, moral, and ascetic tradition created in the Christian East,

28
00:03:40,000 --> 00:03:47,000
 that is, in Palestine, Syria, Egypt, Asia Minor, and Constantinople.

29
00:03:47,000 --> 00:03:54,000
 Everything that comes from this original matrix is considered Orthodox by default.

30
00:03:54,000 --> 00:03:58,000
 This is a very important hermeneutical attitude.

31
00:03:58,000 --> 00:04:07,000
 As a rule, Orthodox theologians necessarily adhere to it, but at the same time they are not aware of it.

32
00:04:07,000 --> 00:04:15,000
 Let us note that in this context, the Western fathers of the Church, and mainly Augustine,

33
00:04:15,000 --> 00:04:20,000
 seem to immediately fall out of sight of Orthodox authors.

34
00:04:20,000 --> 00:04:27,000
 In other words, Orthodoxy in this sense means ancient Eastern Christianity.

35
00:04:27,000 --> 00:04:37,000
 Secondly, by Orthodoxy we mean the Church and tradition which at a certain point in history came into conflict with the Roman Church,

36
00:04:37,000 --> 00:04:43,000
 and the Churches that at that time were subject to its authority.

37
00:04:43,000 --> 00:04:48,000
 After the break in communion between Rome and Orthodoxy, so it is commonly said,

38
00:04:48,000 --> 00:04:52,000
 Orthodoxy began a separate existence.

39
00:04:52,000 --> 00:05:04,000
 For a very long time it was generally accepted that the date of the separation of the Churches of the East and West was 1054.

40
00:05:04,000 --> 00:05:16,000
 Indeed, then the leadership of the Churches of Rome and Constantinople excommunicated each other from Church communion and anathematized each other.

41
00:05:16,000 --> 00:05:23,000
 Since then, these decisions have not been reversed.

42
00:05:23,000 --> 00:05:30,000
 However, in modern times, through the works of Professor Christoph Zutner from Vienna,

43
00:05:30,000 --> 00:05:37,000
 and Klaus Wirwoll from Regensburg and others, this date has been called into question.

44
00:05:37,000 --> 00:05:48,000
 In my opinion, the year 1453 should be considered the date of the division of the Churches.

45
00:05:48,000 --> 00:05:55,000
 Then Constantinople was taken by the Ottomans, and the Eastern Roman Empire ceased to exist.

46
00:05:55,000 --> 00:06:00,000
 This empire outlived the Roman Empire by a thousand years.

47
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:10,000
 At the same time, of the Ottoman triumph, Constantinople was a small city-state with a population of only a few tens of thousands of people.

48
00:06:10,000 --> 00:06:15,000
 However, the symbolic significance of this event was enormous.

49
00:06:15,000 --> 00:06:23,000
 Moreover, the Ottoman sultans considered themselves not destroyers, but successors to the emperors of Constantinople.

50
00:06:23,000 --> 00:06:30,000
 Therefore, they immediately began territorial expansion.

51
00:06:30,000 --> 00:06:45,000
 In my opinion, I propose the date of separation of Churches of East and West is 1453, the fall of Constantinople.

52
00:06:45,000 --> 00:06:52,000
 It is interesting that shortly before the fall of Constantinople in 1439,

53
00:06:52,000 --> 00:06:59,000
 the unity of the Churches of Rome and Constantinople was restored at the Council of Florence.

54
00:06:59,000 --> 00:07:05,000
 Despite the fact that this decision did not have time to undergo the necessary reception,

55
00:07:05,000 --> 00:07:10,000
 formally by 1453 this unity existed.

56
00:07:10,000 --> 00:07:16,000
 Ottoman power took control of Constantinople, the Ottomans refounded the empire,

57
00:07:16,000 --> 00:07:20,000
 from now on they themselves became its center.

58
00:07:20,000 --> 00:07:28,000
 At the same time, they reformated the Orthodox Church.

59
00:07:28,000 --> 00:07:34,000
 In this context, it will be important to define what orthodoxy is.

60
00:07:34,000 --> 00:07:40,000
 The complexity of such a definition lies in the fact that within one term,

61
00:07:40,000 --> 00:07:47,000
 various historical, theological, philosophical, and even political factors are combined.

62
00:07:47,000 --> 00:07:52,000
 Therefore, we will try to simply list such definitions.

63
00:07:52,000 --> 00:08:00,000
 So, first, orthodoxy is Christianity, which in the first centuries of the history of the Church

64
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:05,000
 was formed in the territories of Palestine, Syria, Egypt, Asia Minor,

65
00:08:05,000 --> 00:08:08,000
 and subsequently spread to other countries.

66
00:08:08,000 --> 00:08:14,000
 Second, it's the Church that existed on the territory of the Eastern Roman Empire

67
00:08:14,000 --> 00:08:22,000
 with its capital in Constantinople, as well as those churches on the territory of Syria, Palestine, Egypt, Asia Minor, Russia,

68
00:08:22,000 --> 00:08:29,000
 later in Slavic countries, that until a certain point in history formed a single whole with it,

69
00:08:29,000 --> 00:08:35,000
 and then they continued to be in liturgical and Eucharistic communion.

70
00:08:35,000 --> 00:08:43,000
 These two definitions are based on origin, geography, history, and ecclesiastical organization.

71
00:08:43,000 --> 00:08:51,000
 If we analyze the role of St. Augustine in the context of such definitions of orthodoxy, it will be minimal.

72
00:08:51,000 --> 00:08:58,000
 The reason for this is the fact that Augustine lived in a different historical, geographical, and ecclesiastical context.

73
00:08:58,000 --> 00:09:03,000
 His Christianity was African, Roman, Western.

74
00:09:03,000 --> 00:09:10,000
 As he himself said about himself, "I am an African," "Africanus sum."

75
00:09:10,000 --> 00:09:20,000
 Further, orthodoxy is right, correct, orthodox faith. It's about etymology.

76
00:09:20,000 --> 00:09:30,000
 And also, the Greek word "doxa," which is the basis of the term "orthodox," also means glory, glorification, doxology.

77
00:09:30,000 --> 00:09:35,000
 For instance, "glory to the Father, and to the Son, and to the Holy Spirit" is the same term.

78
00:09:35,000 --> 00:09:41,000
 Therefore, the word "orthodoxy" can mean a way of properly glorifying God.

79
00:09:41,000 --> 00:09:48,000
 This definition of orthodoxy can be called not only theological, but also aesthetic.

80
00:09:48,000 --> 00:09:53,000
 It largely became popular during the postmodern era.

81
00:09:53,000 --> 00:09:58,000
 We also find it by Dostoevsky that the beauty will save our world.

82
00:09:58,000 --> 00:10:07,000
 And finally, this is maybe my personal definitions of what orthodoxy is.

83
00:10:07,000 --> 00:10:18,000
 It is the official confession of faith adopted in the Roman Empire at the level of religious legislation during the Christian period of its history.

84
00:10:18,000 --> 00:10:26,000
 By default, this definition applies to the Ottoman Empire as the legal successor of the Eastern Roman Empire.

85
00:10:26,000 --> 00:10:35,000
 To the Russian Empire, in some forms of orthodox statehood, we have here an icon of the exaltation of the Holy Cross,

86
00:10:35,000 --> 00:10:40,000
 one of the twelve greatest feasts of the Orthodox liturgical year.

87
00:10:40,000 --> 00:10:45,000
 And it is a unique feast which can be called a political feast,

88
00:10:45,000 --> 00:10:51,000
 because it is about the triumph of the Holy Cross in the universe.

89
00:10:51,000 --> 00:10:57,000
 A very important example of what orthodoxy actually is.

90
00:10:57,000 --> 00:11:01,000
 Also, the official confession of faith.

91
00:11:01,000 --> 00:11:08,000
 In this context, consideration of the role of St. Augustine in orthodox theology seems most difficult.

92
00:11:08,000 --> 00:11:22,000
 For instance, the decisions of the Fourth Ecumenical Council 451 in Chalcedon on Christology are based on the theology of Augustine.

93
00:11:22,000 --> 00:11:31,000
 The Council itself does not refer to Augustine, but follows the Christology of the Roman Church of the era of Pope Leo the Great.

94
00:11:31,000 --> 00:11:35,000
 In the doctrine of Christ, he was a follower of Augustine.

95
00:11:35,000 --> 00:11:47,000
 In turn, the decisions of the Seventh Council of Nicea in 787 on iconography rather contradict the logic of Augustine's thinking,

96
00:11:47,000 --> 00:11:51,000
 although he did not write about iconography.

97
00:11:51,000 --> 00:11:58,000
 But rules were part of the official confession of the empire in their respective eras.

98
00:11:58,000 --> 00:12:03,000
 Now, Augustine, is he sent or blessed?

99
00:12:03,000 --> 00:12:08,000
 In orthodox literature, in European languages as well as in Russian,

100
00:12:08,000 --> 00:12:13,000
 it is customary to call Augustine of Hippo blessed.

101
00:12:13,000 --> 00:12:21,000
 Therefore, not only in secular literature, in theology, in philosophy, but also in the liturgical calendar,

102
00:12:21,000 --> 00:12:27,000
 Augustine is called not Saint Augustine, but Blessed Augustine.

103
00:12:27,000 --> 00:12:37,000
 Many theologians and philosophers as well as outside observers presume that this appellation is not accidental.

104
00:12:37,000 --> 00:12:43,000
 They claim that this is a sign that allegedly indicates the following factors.

105
00:12:43,000 --> 00:12:46,000
 First, insufficient holiness.

106
00:12:46,000 --> 00:12:53,000
 Let us remember that in the Roman Catholic Church, there is a difference between saints and blessed.

107
00:12:53,000 --> 00:12:58,000
 A saint is the right person canonized by the Church who is revered by the entire Church.

108
00:12:58,000 --> 00:13:07,000
 It's an obligation for the universal Church to celebrate the memory of a saint.

109
00:13:07,000 --> 00:13:11,000
 He and this person is commemorated as a saint.

110
00:13:11,000 --> 00:13:15,000
 His or her name is placed in the liturgical calendar.

111
00:13:15,000 --> 00:13:23,000
 This veneration and invocation extend to all Church dioceses and regions.

112
00:13:23,000 --> 00:13:30,000
 A blessed is a righteous person whose canonization took place only at the local level.

113
00:13:30,000 --> 00:13:34,000
 He or she is venerated in individual dioceses.

114
00:13:34,000 --> 00:13:42,000
 It is possible that it will be subsequently spread in the whole universal Church,

115
00:13:42,000 --> 00:13:46,000
 but it is also possible that this will not happen.

116
00:13:46,000 --> 00:13:53,000
 The holiness of the blessed is, as it were, incomplete holiness or holiness in the process of waiting.

117
00:13:53,000 --> 00:14:03,000
 The Orthodox Church also distinguishes between local and universal saints, but does not know such terminology.

118
00:14:03,000 --> 00:14:09,000
 There is no formal difference in terminology between saints and blessed.

119
00:14:09,000 --> 00:14:19,000
 However, by analogy taken from the Catholic tradition, many Orthodox believe that Augustine is not a saint who is venerated in Orthodoxy.

120
00:14:19,000 --> 00:14:24,000
 Second, in addition, righteous people who are revered in popular piety,

121
00:14:24,000 --> 00:14:30,000
 but are not formally canonized by the Church, are often called blessed.

122
00:14:30,000 --> 00:14:32,000
 This is modern terminology.

123
00:14:32,000 --> 00:14:42,000
 However, by the logic of anachronism and appropriation, it is often applied to Augustine.

124
00:14:42,000 --> 00:14:45,000
 One more question.

125
00:14:45,000 --> 00:14:51,000
 Blessed, in the proper sense in Orthodoxy, are the saints who have been canonized by the Church

126
00:14:51,000 --> 00:14:56,000
 and are revered at the universal level as fools for Christ's sake.

127
00:14:56,000 --> 00:15:06,000
 In Orthodox ideology, it is generally accepted that holy fools voluntarily assumed the appearance of madness and dementia.

128
00:15:06,000 --> 00:15:12,000
 They have abandoned the full use of their rationality in their mental facilities, faculties,

129
00:15:12,000 --> 00:15:16,000
 in order to acquire humility and avoid praise and pride.

130
00:15:16,000 --> 00:15:24,000
 Although neither Augustine nor, for instance, Saint Jerome is also called blessed in the Orthodox tradition,

131
00:15:24,000 --> 00:15:27,000
 they were ever perceived as holy fools.

132
00:15:27,000 --> 00:15:33,000
 Calling them blessed helps to take their theologian legacy with some skepticism.

133
00:15:33,000 --> 00:15:38,000
 Automatically, if you say Saint Augustine is only blessed people,

134
00:15:38,000 --> 00:15:47,000
 start thinking about those fools in Christ who were a little bit strange people

135
00:15:47,000 --> 00:15:51,000
 and didn't do and didn't practice theology.

136
00:15:51,000 --> 00:15:59,000
 It is very difficult to enter discussion because as soon as they hear this notion of being blessed,

137
00:15:59,000 --> 00:16:08,000
 they stop reflection on the theological meanings and teachings of Augustine.

138
00:16:08,000 --> 00:16:16,000
 This is some kind of semantic anachronism that also works.

139
00:16:16,000 --> 00:16:24,000
 It is important to note that the very name blessed in relation to Augustine in Orthodoxy is a trace of deep archaism.

140
00:16:24,000 --> 00:16:31,000
 The fact is that the name of Augustine has appeared in various legends about saints over the centuries.

141
00:16:31,000 --> 00:16:35,000
 It is found in ancient editions of the Psalter.

142
00:16:35,000 --> 00:16:40,000
 However, such mention of him has always been abstract.

143
00:16:40,000 --> 00:16:49,000
 In the strict sense of the word, neither Augustine nor, for instance, Jerome were known in the Orthodox world.

144
00:16:49,000 --> 00:16:54,000
 The name of both was absent from the Orthodox liturgical calendar.

145
00:16:54,000 --> 00:16:59,000
 Theologian and mystic reformer of piety and Eucharistic life of Greek Orthodoxy,

146
00:16:59,000 --> 00:17:07,000
 Nicodemus the Agile-Wright, supplemented the liturgical calendar and added the names of Augustine and Jerome to it,

147
00:17:07,000 --> 00:17:14,000
 but it was in the beginning of the 19th century.

148
00:17:14,000 --> 00:17:22,000
 It doesn't mean anything because the Orthodox liturgical calendar at that time was simply incomplete.

149
00:17:22,000 --> 00:17:33,000
 But some people think that this is the main proof that Augustine is somebody who is not considered a saint in the Orthodox world.

150
00:17:33,000 --> 00:17:40,000
 Moreover, the very date of memory of Saint Augustine was chosen arbitrarily.

151
00:17:40,000 --> 00:17:48,000
 June 15 does not have any connection with the biography of the saints.

152
00:17:48,000 --> 00:17:57,000
 Probably there was an abbot on the Mount Athos in Greece who celebrated his birthday or something else like this.

153
00:17:57,000 --> 00:18:07,000
 And that's why they put the memory of Saint Augustine on the same day.

154
00:18:07,000 --> 00:18:18,000
 The archaic Tito blast is a consequence of such acceptance into the calendar without any official reception or theological reflection.

155
00:18:18,000 --> 00:18:26,000
 It is interesting that in modern Greek Orthodoxy, Augustine is sometimes called Eros, sacred.

156
00:18:26,000 --> 00:18:33,000
 That is how saints are called in the Greek tradition, saints whose memory is especially important for the Church.

157
00:18:33,000 --> 00:18:47,000
 For instance, John Chrysostom is called sacred, and his veneration in Eastern Orthodoxy is a long-standing and extremely important tradition.

158
00:18:47,000 --> 00:18:55,000
 Here we have three authors I prepared, analyzing the role of Saint Augustine.

159
00:18:55,000 --> 00:19:08,000
 Here I would like to put the picture of Nicodemus Agiorite, who put the name of Augustine into the liturgical calendar.

160
00:19:08,000 --> 00:19:18,000
 He was a very interesting theologian. He was also a missionary ascetic.

161
00:19:18,000 --> 00:19:26,000
 He was one of the pioneers of frequent communion, because before him in Greek Orthodoxy,

162
00:19:26,000 --> 00:19:41,000
 they got communion maybe once a year, once in some months, during Easter maybe, but he was a pioneer of continuous communion.

163
00:19:41,000 --> 00:19:44,000
 And that's very interesting that he put the name.

164
00:19:44,000 --> 00:19:50,000
 And he was also one of the publishers and authors of the Philokalia edition in Greek language.

165
00:19:50,000 --> 00:20:01,000
 So it's very interesting that he got in touch with the memory of Saint Augustine.

166
00:20:01,000 --> 00:20:06,000
 And now, what I would like to mention.

167
00:20:06,000 --> 00:20:12,000
 Throughout its history, the Orthodox tradition has existed in specific contexts.

168
00:20:12,000 --> 00:20:21,000
 The main factors that radically changed the mode of existence of Orthodoxy were the revolution in Russia in 1917,

169
00:20:21,000 --> 00:20:26,000
 the Aegean Minor disaster, that's in the year 20 of the 20th century,

170
00:20:26,000 --> 00:20:32,000
 Pan-Arabism, and the beginning of the collapse of Levantine Christianity.

171
00:20:32,000 --> 00:20:36,000
 In the 20th century, Orthodox Christianity underwent enormous changes.

172
00:20:36,000 --> 00:20:39,000
 I would identify these three factors.

173
00:20:39,000 --> 00:20:44,000
 As a result of the Bolshevik revolution in Russia, not only the monarchy fell,

174
00:20:44,000 --> 00:20:48,000
 but also the period of Orthodox statehood ended.

175
00:20:48,000 --> 00:20:53,000
 The Orthodox political system, which theologians call the Constantinian period,

176
00:20:53,000 --> 00:20:59,000
 we saw the icon with some emperors having the Holy Cross,

177
00:20:59,000 --> 00:21:06,000
 it was the best image of what we call the Constantinian period in the church history,

178
00:21:06,000 --> 00:21:09,000
 has become a thing of the past.

179
00:21:09,000 --> 00:21:15,000
 As a result of the subsequent civil war, millions of Orthodox Christians found themselves abroad

180
00:21:15,000 --> 00:21:19,000
 and began a new life in the countries of the Western world.

181
00:21:19,000 --> 00:21:24,000
 The second factor was the so-called Aegean Minor catastrophe,

182
00:21:24,000 --> 00:21:32,000
 when, as a result of the Greek-Turkish war, there was an exchange of populations between Turkey and Greece.

183
00:21:32,000 --> 00:21:39,000
 The collapse of the Ottoman Empire resulted in the displacement of millions of Orthodox Greeks towards Greece.

184
00:21:39,000 --> 00:21:46,000
 Since the latter could not accept such a number of immigrants, many of them moved to North America.

185
00:21:46,000 --> 00:21:51,000
 And it is how a huge Orthodox diaspora arose in the Western world.

186
00:21:51,000 --> 00:21:57,000
 Finally, the collapse of the colonial system, the emergence of the ideology of Pan-Arabism

187
00:21:57,000 --> 00:22:02,000
 and Arab nationalism also contributed to the fact that numerous Orthodox Christians,

188
00:22:02,000 --> 00:22:08,000
 who had previously lived for centuries in the Middle East, particularly in Egypt,

189
00:22:08,000 --> 00:22:12,000
 were forced to leave their places of former residence.

190
00:22:12,000 --> 00:22:20,000
 This is how a new era was formed, when the Orthodox world began to come into close contact with the Western world.

191
00:22:20,000 --> 00:22:29,000
 As often happens in globalization processes, the question of self-identification has arisen.

192
00:22:29,000 --> 00:22:34,000
 It was a gradual process. As a symbolic starting point,

193
00:22:34,000 --> 00:22:41,000
 I would like to indicate the expulsion of Russian intellectuals from Russia by Lenin.

194
00:22:41,000 --> 00:22:49,000
 And that was for the first time in history that Orthodox intellectuals found themselves

195
00:22:49,000 --> 00:22:53,000
 in a completely Roman Catholic or Protestant environment.

196
00:22:53,000 --> 00:22:56,000
 An intense process of reflection began.

197
00:22:56,000 --> 00:23:05,000
 The question of how, in fact, Orthodoxy differs from Western Christianity has acquired a particularly extreme actuality.

198
00:23:05,000 --> 00:23:14,000
 To summarize, we can briefly outline what happened at that time.

199
00:23:14,000 --> 00:23:21,000
 Orthodox began to be aware of their belonging to the Church.

200
00:23:21,000 --> 00:23:26,000
 According to the text of the Creed, it was one holy Catholic and apostolic Church.

201
00:23:26,000 --> 00:23:30,000
 However, Western Christians could say the same about themselves.

202
00:23:30,000 --> 00:23:38,000
 It was necessary to find such a special characteristic to identify one's own tradition.

203
00:23:38,000 --> 00:23:43,000
 And this one was Church of the Fathers.

204
00:23:43,000 --> 00:23:45,000
 What means Church of the Fathers?

205
00:23:45,000 --> 00:23:58,000
 If we go to the Ecumenical Councils, we can find a canon from the Fifth Ecumenical Council, 553,

206
00:23:58,000 --> 00:24:05,000
 where it is said, "We follow in everything the Holy Fathers and teachers of the Holy Church of God,

207
00:24:05,000 --> 00:24:12,000
 that is, Athanasius, Hilary, Basil, Gregory the Theologian, Gregory of Nyssa, Ambrose, Theophilus,

208
00:24:12,000 --> 00:24:15,000
 John Chrysostom, Cyril, Augustine, Proclus, Leo.

209
00:24:15,000 --> 00:24:24,000
 And we accept everything that is written, and they explain about the right faith and the condemnation of heretics."

210
00:24:24,000 --> 00:24:29,000
 Here we see that Augustine and Leo represent Western Christianity.

211
00:24:29,000 --> 00:24:35,000
 The other fathers mostly the Eastern one.

