00:24:35,000 --> 00:24:41,000
 It is very important that the name Augustine is mentioned in this ancient canon,

213
00:24:41,000 --> 00:24:50,000
 and in some way it becomes an obligation to have respect towards Saint Augustine.

214
00:24:50,000 --> 00:24:55,000
 But why he is mentioned in this context is unclear,

215
00:24:55,000 --> 00:25:06,000
 because Saint Augustine was not known in the Orthodox Christianity.

216
00:25:06,000 --> 00:25:14,000
 And that's why it is important to see how some Orthodox theologians treat Augustine,

217
00:25:14,000 --> 00:25:16,000
 what they say about him.

218
00:25:16,000 --> 00:25:25,000
 First, I took one of the Serbian and Russian theologians, Ambrose Pogodin.

219
00:25:25,000 --> 00:25:35,000
 It's very important that he got this double Orthodox origin from Serbia and France,

220
00:25:35,000 --> 00:25:39,000
 and also served in different countries.

221
00:25:39,000 --> 00:25:48,000
 In his article on Saint Augustine, called "Orthodox Church and Blessed Augustine,"

222
00:25:48,000 --> 00:25:52,000
 Ambrose Pogodin outlines his perception of Augustine.

223
00:25:52,000 --> 00:25:59,000
 In doing so, he responds to the harsh criticism of the theology of Augustine,

224
00:25:59,000 --> 00:26:07,000
 which was carried out by certain representatives of the Greek Orthodox conservative circles of the 20th century.

225
00:26:07,000 --> 00:26:16,000
 It is characteristic that already in the title of his article, Ambrose calls Augustine "blessed."

226
00:26:16,000 --> 00:26:23,000
 This means that he is not ready to equate Augustine with other ancient fathers of the Church,

227
00:26:23,000 --> 00:26:27,000
 who are usually, as I said, called "saints."

228
00:26:27,000 --> 00:26:33,000
 According to Ambrose, the Greek theologian Michael Atskou calls Augustine

229
00:26:33,000 --> 00:26:40,000
 "the father of all heretics," the cause of Roman Catholic and Protestant errors.

230
00:26:40,000 --> 00:26:44,000
 He also believes that Augustine is not one of the Orthodox saints,

231
00:26:44,000 --> 00:26:48,000
 and Ambrose Pogodin tries to respond to him.

232
00:26:48,000 --> 00:26:55,000
 The first issue that Pogodin considers is Augustine's teaching on grace and predestination.

233
00:26:55,000 --> 00:27:03,000
 In doing so, he immediately refers his reader to the work of Seraphim Rose,

234
00:27:03,000 --> 00:27:07,000
 another Orthodox theologian of the past century.

235
00:27:07,000 --> 00:27:13,000
 At the same time, he notes that he intends to correct, to complement Rose,

236
00:27:13,000 --> 00:27:18,000
 but also to distance himself from him.

237
00:27:18,000 --> 00:27:22,000
 Ambrose interprets Augustine's teaching on grace as follows.

238
00:27:22,000 --> 00:27:26,000
 "After the fall, man needs grace. However, he can reject grace.

239
00:27:26,000 --> 00:27:30,000
 Grace strengthens the saints in their heroism," states Pogodin.

240
00:27:30,000 --> 00:27:36,000
 In essence, predestination and foreknowledge of God in Augustine's understanding coincide.

241
00:27:36,000 --> 00:27:44,000
 Very strange conclusion, because we know that this distinction between predestination and prescience

242
00:27:44,000 --> 00:27:51,000
 is one of the most important things in the grace theology of Saint Augustine.

243
00:27:51,000 --> 00:28:00,000
 It was also very typical after the fall, the whole development of dogma in the whole Western traditions,

244
00:28:00,000 --> 00:28:06,000
 and we know about it, but he apparently didn't want to know about it.

245
00:28:06,000 --> 00:28:14,000
 It's a very special methodological, it's an emanatical attitude.

246
00:28:14,000 --> 00:28:20,000
 At the same time, Pogodin believes that the Roman Catholic Church rejects Augustine's teaching on grace.

247
00:28:20,000 --> 00:28:27,000
 Why? Since Catholic ethics is built on a person's acquisition of merit before God,

248
00:28:27,000 --> 00:28:31,000
 and because John Calvin subsequently taught about predestination.

249
00:28:31,000 --> 00:28:37,000
 So probably Ambrose Pogodin was a very good specialist in church fathers,

250
00:28:37,000 --> 00:28:41,000
 but he didn't study Western tradition.

251
00:28:41,000 --> 00:28:51,000
 That's why he came to such conclusions that Catholics did reject Saint Augustine,

252
00:28:51,000 --> 00:28:56,000
 and that John Calvin is right, he taught about predestination.

253
00:28:56,000 --> 00:29:03,000
 Ambrose refers to his colleague, Seraphim Rose, who argued that Augustine's teaching was orthodox,

254
00:29:03,000 --> 00:29:09,000
 but it was characterized by exaggerated language, which gave rise to incorrect interpretations.

255
00:29:09,000 --> 00:29:15,000
 Pogodin makes a short excursion into the research of Russian theologians of the 19th century on Augustine,

256
00:29:15,000 --> 00:29:20,000
 and concludes that the Greek fathers of the church were dogmatics,

257
00:29:20,000 --> 00:29:24,000
 while Blessed Augustine is an excellent moralist.

258
00:29:24,000 --> 00:29:32,000
 Very interesting remark, because I would say Pelagius was a moralist, but not said Augustine.

259
00:29:32,000 --> 00:29:38,000
 Nevertheless, for Ambrose Pogodin, Augustine was a moralist.

260
00:29:38,000 --> 00:29:42,000
 That's very important, because such clichés are still alive.

261
00:29:42,000 --> 00:29:47,000
 If you speak with an orthodox Christian who knows about Saint Augustine,

262
00:29:47,000 --> 00:29:53,000
 he will probably respond the same thing.

263
00:29:53,000 --> 00:29:58,000
 The second question of Augustine's theology which Pogodin discusses

264
00:29:58,000 --> 00:30:02,000
 is the famous question of the procession of the Holy Spirit.

265
00:30:02,000 --> 00:30:10,000
 Here, his answer is, "Augustine's doctrine of the Trinity is not formulated with precision.

266
00:30:10,000 --> 00:30:12,000
 It is incomplete."

267
00:30:12,000 --> 00:30:19,000
 Sometimes I read Augustine's work on the Trinitate, on Trinity,

268
00:30:19,000 --> 00:30:23,000
 and I doubt whether it is incomplete.

269
00:30:23,000 --> 00:30:31,000
 We see this hermeneutical attitude, which is a very special one.

270
00:30:31,000 --> 00:30:35,000
 Unlike the doctrine of grace and predestination,

271
00:30:35,000 --> 00:30:40,000
 where Ambrose simply puts his own point of view into Augustine's mouth,

272
00:30:40,000 --> 00:30:46,000
 it is not possible for him to do the same on the issue of the procession of the Holy Spirit.

273
00:30:46,000 --> 00:30:51,000
 Subsequent tradition, and most importantly, the Carolingian theologians themselves,

274
00:30:51,000 --> 00:30:53,000
 refer to Augustine in this matter.

275
00:30:53,000 --> 00:30:55,000
 It is too obvious.

276
00:30:55,000 --> 00:31:07,000
 That's why Pogodin quotes photos of Constantinople, Archbishop of Constantinople in the 9th century,

277
00:31:07,000 --> 00:31:13,000
 who says that works of Augustine were probably falsified.

278
00:31:13,000 --> 00:31:19,000
 He didn't teach about filioque or about the double procession of the Holy Spirit

279
00:31:19,000 --> 00:31:24,000
 from the father and from the son, but his works were falsified.

280
00:31:24,000 --> 00:31:30,000
 It's an interesting opinion, which matched probably for that time,

281
00:31:30,000 --> 00:31:38,000
 but Pogodin, he is a theologian from the 20th century, and he still repeats this opinion.

282
00:31:38,000 --> 00:31:52,000
 Another theologian about whom I would like to speak is a Greek theologian from Boston,

283
00:31:52,000 --> 00:31:54,000
 George Papadimitriou.

284
00:31:54,000 --> 00:32:00,000
 What is interesting about him, already the title of his article,

285
00:32:00,000 --> 00:32:03,000
 "St. Augustine in the Greek Orthodox Tradition."

286
00:32:03,000 --> 00:32:10,000
 He rightly points out that within the framework of a single Orthodox Christianity,

287
00:32:10,000 --> 00:32:13,000
 various independent traditions have already formed,

288
00:32:13,000 --> 00:32:17,000
 therefore the theology of each must be studied separately.

289
00:32:17,000 --> 00:32:26,000
 If we speak in detail, we have to speak about St. Augustine in Greek Orthodox Tradition,

290
00:32:26,000 --> 00:32:34,000
 Serbian, in Russian, maybe there is also a small Polish Orthodox Church with its own theologians,

291
00:32:34,000 --> 00:32:36,000
 but we have no time.

292
00:32:36,000 --> 00:32:41,000
 Anyway, we see that in his article he already points to it,

293
00:32:41,000 --> 00:32:44,000
 that St. Augustine in the Greek Orthodox Tradition.

294
00:32:46,000 --> 00:32:52,000
 Papadimitriou consistently examines the place of Augustine in the works of those authors

295
00:32:52,000 --> 00:32:59,000
 who, in his opinion, can obviously be considered as a kind of topoi of Greek Orthodox history.

296
00:32:59,000 --> 00:33:04,000
 This is Photios of Constantinople, we spoke about him,

297
00:33:04,000 --> 00:33:11,000
 and Gregory Palamas, teacher of grace in the Orthodox Tradition,

298
00:33:11,000 --> 00:33:21,000
 and also that this new personality in this Augustinian study in the Orthodox world,

299
00:33:21,000 --> 00:33:27,000
 the patriarch of Constantinople, the first Ottoman patriarch, Gennadius Holarius.

300
00:33:27,000 --> 00:33:30,000
 After this, he moves on to the modern period.

301
00:33:30,000 --> 00:33:34,000
 The conclusion of this review is also quite characteristic,

302
00:33:34,000 --> 00:33:40,000
 and the periodization is very typical.

303
00:33:41,000 --> 00:33:43,000
 For instance,

304
00:33:43,000 --> 00:34:02,000
 he also speaks about Marcus of Ephesus and the Union of Florence.

305
00:34:02,000 --> 00:34:11,000
 What is important, speaking about the Council of Florence,

306
00:34:11,000 --> 00:34:18,000
 Papadimitriou admits that Augustine was a pro-Latin theologian.

307
00:34:18,000 --> 00:34:22,000
 And in this moment, some kind of new confession is emerging,

308
00:34:22,000 --> 00:34:29,000
 because here Augustine's authority is very limited by Papadimitriou,

309
00:34:29,000 --> 00:34:36,000
 and he says if his theology, or if Augustine in his theology,

310
00:34:36,000 --> 00:34:38,000
 differs in some way from others,

311
00:34:38,000 --> 00:34:44,000
 Augustine had to be subordinated to the general teaching of the Orthodox Church.

312
00:34:44,000 --> 00:34:49,000
 We see this balance between West and East,

313
00:34:49,000 --> 00:34:57,000
 which is very important to understand how Orthodox theology speaks about Saint Augustine.

314
00:34:57,000 --> 00:35:03,000
 Apparently, we have here, under the pen of Papadimitriou,

315
00:35:03,000 --> 00:35:06,000
 some kind of instrumentalization of Augustine,

316
00:35:06,000 --> 00:35:09,000
 characteristic of all subsequent Orthodoxy.

317
00:35:09,000 --> 00:35:12,000
 There is no reception of his theology,

318
00:35:12,000 --> 00:35:16,000
 but a conditional reference to it is necessary,

319
00:35:16,000 --> 00:35:21,000
 since it proves the utterance of the Orthodox to patristic authorities.

320
00:35:21,000 --> 00:35:27,000
 Speaking about the role of Augustine in the modern Greek Orthodox tradition,

321
00:35:27,000 --> 00:35:31,000
 Papadimitriou also mentions that it was Nicodemus the Agiorite

322
00:35:31,000 --> 00:35:35,000
 who included the name of Augustine in the liturgical calendar of saints.

323
00:35:35,000 --> 00:35:42,000
 The name of Nicodemus, as I said, is associated with the revival of religious life,

324
00:35:42,000 --> 00:35:49,000
 and Papadimitriou also says that Nicodemus wrote about Augustine with all prize-worthy epithets.

325
00:35:49,000 --> 00:35:55,000
 Papadimitriou lists several authors who have called for the integration of Augustine

326
00:35:55,000 --> 00:35:59,000
 into the life and theology of the Orthodox Church today.

327
00:35:59,000 --> 00:36:05,000
 He also writes that some modern Greek theologians subjected Augustine to harsh criticism.

328
00:36:05,000 --> 00:36:10,000
 Thus, one involuntarily gets the impression that Orthodox piety,

329
00:36:10,000 --> 00:36:16,000
 Nicodemus, and the monastic tradition obliges to respect the authority of Augustine,

330
00:36:16,000 --> 00:36:22,000
 while Orthodox theology, as theology, Romanides and other theologians,

331
00:36:22,000 --> 00:36:28,000
 characteristic of the modern Greek Christian traditions,

332
00:36:28,000 --> 00:36:35,000
 judges Augustine on the basis of their own criteria, methodology, and hermeneutics.

333
00:36:35,000 --> 00:36:38,000
 The question arises about the criteria.

334
00:36:38,000 --> 00:36:42,000
 Should Augustine's theology be taken as a matrix for conclusions

335
00:36:42,000 --> 00:36:47,000
 about the theology of later times, or vice versa?

336
00:36:47,000 --> 00:36:57,000
 One more theologian, it's very famous in the English-speaking Orthodox world,

337
00:36:57,000 --> 00:36:59,000
 Seraphim Ross.

338
00:36:59,000 --> 00:37:05,000
 He was very knowledgeable about modern Western philosophy and culture.

339
00:37:05,000 --> 00:37:09,000
 His perception of Augustine is extremely interesting.

340
00:37:09,000 --> 00:37:13,000
 He dedicated a separate small monograph to Augustine.

341
00:37:13,000 --> 00:37:19,000
 The reception of Seraphim is important because it is not just theological treatise,

342
00:37:19,000 --> 00:37:23,000
 but a kind of exercise in piety.

343
00:37:23,000 --> 00:37:27,000
 Ross consistently strives to remind his modern Orthodox reader

344
00:37:27,000 --> 00:37:29,000
 of the good name of Augustine.

345
00:37:29,000 --> 00:37:32,000
 The audience he was addressing was Western.

346
00:37:32,000 --> 00:37:36,000
 During the Iron Curtain period, his work simply could not be accessible

347
00:37:36,000 --> 00:37:39,000
 to readers in most Orthodox countries.

348
00:37:39,000 --> 00:37:43,000
 Unlike Omros Pogodin, who was a scholar in patristics and translator

349
00:37:43,000 --> 00:37:47,000
 of the Church Fathers, Seraphim Ross obviously mastered

350
00:37:47,000 --> 00:37:49,000
 contemporary philosophical issues.

351
00:37:49,000 --> 00:37:54,000
 He studied modern religiosity, sects, wrote on philosophical issues,

352
00:37:54,000 --> 00:37:59,000
 and was keenly interested in everything happening in the world.

353
00:37:59,000 --> 00:38:05,000
 This was to give his work on Augustine and Orthodoxy special interest.

