00:45:57,000 --> 00:46:01,000
 should guarantee Augustine's place in Orthodox theology.

451
00:46:01,000 --> 00:46:07,000
 You also named the Orthodox thinkers who have been engaged in the study of Augustine,

452
00:46:07,000 --> 00:46:13,000
 but regretted to find that these attempts have so far failed to do justice

453
00:46:13,000 --> 00:46:16,000
 to the true worth of Augustine's thought.

454
00:46:16,000 --> 00:46:23,000
 Having outlined these key points, there are a few areas into which

455
00:46:23,000 --> 00:46:26,000
 I'd like to make further inquiry.

456
00:46:26,000 --> 00:46:31,000
 The first is about the place of the Saints and the Fathers

457
00:46:31,000 --> 00:46:35,000
 in the liturgy and theology of the Orthodox Church.

458
00:46:35,000 --> 00:46:42,000
 To my understanding, liturgy and theology are absolutely inseparable in Orthodoxy,

459
00:46:42,000 --> 00:46:50,000
 given that both genuine faith and Orthodox theology are embedded in the Byzantine Rite.

460
00:46:50,000 --> 00:46:56,000
 Although the Rite is celebrated in the vernaculars of the different peoples,

461
00:46:56,000 --> 00:47:01,000
 it goes back to the same authors who are Saints and Fathers of the Church.

462
00:47:01,000 --> 00:47:08,000
 Here, I think, lies the significance of the Saints and Fathers in Orthodox life.

463
00:47:08,000 --> 00:47:15,000
 I'd like to inquire further into the area of Sainthood in Orthodoxy.

464
00:47:15,000 --> 00:47:23,000
 In your lecture, you suggested the reason for Augustine being called "Blessed" rather than "Saint"

465
00:47:23,000 --> 00:47:32,000
 is due to a complex web of factors involving a paradoxical mix of archaism and anachronism.

466
00:47:32,000 --> 00:47:38,000
 You mentioned that there's no formal difference between the terms "Blessed" and "Saint".

467
00:47:38,000 --> 00:47:43,000
 Also, you brought to our attention that the title used for Augustine is somewhat different

468
00:47:43,000 --> 00:47:46,000
 in the different Orthodox communities.

469
00:47:46,000 --> 00:47:51,000
 For whereas, he is usually referred to as "Blessed" in Russian Orthodoxy,

470
00:47:51,000 --> 00:47:56,000
 he is called "Sacred" in the Greek Church.

471
00:47:56,000 --> 00:47:59,000
 My question is twofold.

472
00:47:59,000 --> 00:48:06,000
 Is the idea of Sainthood in Orthodoxy something subject to local variations?

473
00:48:06,000 --> 00:48:12,000
 If that is the case, how does this square with the practice in the liturgy of the Orthodox Church

474
00:48:12,000 --> 00:48:18,000
 where lists of Saints are read out during the Divine Liturgy?

475
00:48:18,000 --> 00:48:27,000
 I understand the liturgy is common and shared among the Orthodox communities

476
00:48:27,000 --> 00:48:31,000
 in different geographical locations.

477
00:48:31,000 --> 00:48:39,000
 Also, I'd like to understand whether the idea of Sainthood in Orthodoxy is a greater concept,

478
00:48:39,000 --> 00:48:48,000
 as in whether a father may be more authoritative than another father.

479
00:48:48,000 --> 00:48:59,000
 And if that is the case, does the degree of authority depend on the place of a particular father,

480
00:48:59,000 --> 00:49:04,000
 how it is occupied in the liturgy?

481
00:49:04,000 --> 00:49:13,000
 For example, like John Chrysostom, he has got a Divine Liturgy that is named after him.

482
00:49:13,000 --> 00:49:21,000
 Would that for some reason mean that he is more authoritative than some other fathers

483
00:49:21,000 --> 00:49:25,000
 who are mentioned otherwise?

484
00:49:25,000 --> 00:49:33,000
 Coming from a Protestant background, in which denominationalism is a key phenomenon,

485
00:49:33,000 --> 00:49:39,000
 I think Protestants can learn a lot from the Orthodox understanding of communion

486
00:49:39,000 --> 00:49:45,000
 founded upon unity in liturgical practice.

487
00:49:45,000 --> 00:49:53,000
 My second area of interest is about the turn to logistic heritage.

488
00:49:53,000 --> 00:50:05,000
 You have mentioned a few names of Orthodox authors who have done study on Augustine.

489
00:50:05,000 --> 00:50:16,000
 You told us about Ambrose Pagodin, Seraphim Rose, George Papadimitriou, and John Maksimovich.

490
00:50:16,000 --> 00:50:29,000
 It seems that in the last century, there has been a period of renewal in the study of patristics in various quarters.

491
00:50:29,000 --> 00:50:39,000
 In Roman Catholicism, there was the Fresou-Simon movement, or I guess it should be "resourcement" in English,

492
00:50:39,000 --> 00:50:45,000
 that emphasised Church reform through a return to patristic sources.

493
00:50:45,000 --> 00:50:52,000
 Similarly, in Protestantism, there are theologians like T.F. Torrance and Colin Gunton

494
00:50:52,000 --> 00:50:58,000
 who were engaged in retrieving patristic resources in their doctrinal works.

495
00:50:58,000 --> 00:51:05,000
 One of the Fresou-Simon theologians, Henri de Lubac, goes so far as to say that

496
00:51:05,000 --> 00:51:16,000
 "Each time in our West, that Christian renewal has flourished under the sign of the Fathers."

497
00:51:16,000 --> 00:51:23,000
 Being certain that these efforts in returning to patristic heritage have been as rewarding,

498
00:51:23,000 --> 00:51:26,000
 if not more so in the Eastern Church as in the West,

499
00:51:26,000 --> 00:51:34,000
 I am interested in learning about the fruits borne by embracing the identity of the Church of the Father.

500
00:51:34,000 --> 00:51:41,000
 My question is, what does the Orthodox self-understanding being the Church of the Fathers mean

501
00:51:41,000 --> 00:51:49,000
 in terms of practical life and piety on the one hand, and output in theological writings on the other?

502
00:51:49,000 --> 00:51:57,000
 I've been interested in looking at this more broadly, going beyond Augustine,

503
00:51:57,000 --> 00:52:07,000
 so that like how the Fathers have been appropriated in general in Orthodoxy during the last century.

504
00:52:07,000 --> 00:52:17,000
 Finally, I'd like to return to Augustine, more specifically about the place of Augustine in an East-West dialogue.

505
00:52:17,000 --> 00:52:23,000
 In the description of this lecture, you have raised the question,

506
00:52:23,000 --> 00:52:32,000
 "Is it generally legitimate to divide the representative of patristic into East and West?"

507
00:52:32,000 --> 00:52:37,000
 I'd like to hear a little bit more from you on this question.

508
00:52:37,000 --> 00:52:46,000
 Responding to the common way of dividing patristic Trinitarian doctrines into Eastern and Western formulations,

509
00:52:46,000 --> 00:52:52,000
 Lewis Ayres has demonstrated that such an approach cannot be maintained.

510
00:52:52,000 --> 00:53:01,000
 And in your lecture, you have alluded to the relevance of Augustine's theology to Orthodox Christianity.

511
00:53:01,000 --> 00:53:04,000
 The question I'd like to pursue is this.

512
00:53:04,000 --> 00:53:15,000
 By singling out Augustine in this lecture, presumably because he is often regarded as the most influential among the Western Fathers,

513
00:53:15,000 --> 00:53:29,000
 what would you anticipate to be the unique contribution that he could make to Orthodox Christianity by a more vigorous study into his thoughts?

514
00:53:29,000 --> 00:53:35,000
 I think I've raised some questions to keep this dialogue going for a while.

515
00:53:35,000 --> 00:53:39,000
 I look forward to being enlightened by your response.

516
00:53:39,000 --> 00:53:45,000
 Before then, I'd like to once again express my gratitude to you, Dr. Sokolovsky,

517
00:53:45,000 --> 00:53:55,000
 for coming up with this very meaningful topic on Augustine of Hippo and the Western Fathers in Orthodox theology and piety.

518
00:54:06,000 --> 00:54:16,000
 Thank you so much, Dr. Sokolovsky, for giving us such an inspiring lecture and Andrew's response.

519
00:54:16,000 --> 00:54:27,000
 In order to deepen our dialogue between East and West, I would like to invite our two speakers to come forward again

520
00:54:27,000 --> 00:54:38,000
 so that we will first have a dialogue session between these two speakers before we open the floor for their Q&A session.

521
00:54:38,000 --> 00:54:40,000
 So, please come forward.

522
00:54:40,000 --> 00:55:05,000
 [Pause]

523
00:55:05,000 --> 00:55:23,000
 So, after Andrew's response, maybe Dr. Sokolovsky, do you have some immediate response you would like to give or you would like to answer Andrew's questions?

524
00:55:23,000 --> 00:55:36,000
 Yes, maybe it's very important that you mention that this revival of patristics in Orthodox Christianity was not alone.

525
00:55:36,000 --> 00:55:50,000
 It was linked with the same revival of patristics in the Catholic Church and also in the Protestant churches and community.

526
00:55:50,000 --> 00:55:56,000
 We Orthodox often forget about it, we don't know about it.

527
00:55:56,000 --> 00:56:03,000
 Also, if we speak about liturgical renewal, that's the same story.

528
00:56:03,000 --> 00:56:26,000
 And that was the immediate fruit or result of the meeting of different Christians from different denominations, which happened after these three crucial immigration processes in the Western and Eastern world.

529
00:56:26,000 --> 00:56:29,000
 It's very important, thank you very much.

530
00:56:29,000 --> 00:56:54,000
 What is maybe typical for the Orthodox tradition is that discovering the role of the fathers, Orthodox theologians start speaking or start making or asking who is the church father?

531
00:56:54,000 --> 00:56:58,000
 What is the era of the fathers?

532
00:56:58,000 --> 00:57:07,000
 And they came to the conclusion that the era of the fathers of the church never ends.

533
00:57:07,000 --> 00:57:15,000
 And that's maybe very typical or the crucial point of the Orthodox understanding of fathers.

534
00:57:15,000 --> 00:57:33,000
 It means that every time, every moment, every moment in human history, in every moment, Orthodox Church has to be able to produce new fathers of the church.

535
00:57:33,000 --> 00:57:50,000
 From an hermeneutical point of view, it's problematic because we know more or less the patristic era stops with the emergence or with the arrival of Islam.

536
00:57:50,000 --> 00:58:00,000
 Why? I didn't find any sufficient explanation personally, I think, because the whole world view was broken.

537
00:58:00,000 --> 00:58:17,000
 The fathers were sure that a complete Christianization of our world started and soon or later the whole world will be Christian.

538
00:58:17,000 --> 00:58:27,000
 And then, in that human history follows a logical step towards this Christian, pan-Christian unity.

539
00:58:27,000 --> 00:58:38,000
 And then suddenly a new religion emerges and starts conquering new faithful territories.

540
00:58:38,000 --> 00:58:44,000
 And especially Eastern Christianity has to resign from all these plans.

541
00:58:44,000 --> 00:58:50,000
 And I think that was the end of the patristic era.

542
00:58:50,000 --> 00:58:57,000
 A very interesting question about saints, because for me personally it's very important.

543
00:58:57,000 --> 00:59:08,000
 As the pandemic began, I had no opportunity as all of us to do academic work offline, so I started writing on saints.

544
00:59:08,000 --> 00:59:21,000
 And it seemed to me that I was sure I knew a lot about saints and I discovered that I knew quite a few about saints.

545
00:59:21,000 --> 00:59:33,000
 And one of those saints was Saint Augustine. I knew about him, but his personal approach to holiness in our world was very interesting

546
00:59:33,000 --> 00:59:38,000
 because he also lived in a very critical moment of human history.

547
00:59:38,000 --> 00:59:46,000
 I discovered a lot of very precious and rare saints, for instance, Martyrs of Alexandria,

548
00:59:46,000 --> 00:59:50,000
 who died during the pandemics in the middle of the 3rd century.

549
00:59:50,000 --> 01:00:03,000
 As Bishop Dionysius the Great of Alexandria, he helped sick people during the pandemic and all pagans escaped the city.

550
01:00:03,000 --> 01:00:07,000
 And many Christians died because of this social work.

551
01:00:07,000 --> 01:00:16,000
 And Dionysius of Alexandria canonized immediately all those martyrs, as he called them, of Alexandria.

552
01:00:16,000 --> 01:00:18,000
 A very interesting example.

553
01:00:18,000 --> 01:00:28,000
 You mentioned liturgy and sainthood. We used to do only two Eucharistic prayers in our tradition.

554
01:00:28,000 --> 01:00:34,000
 One is called St. John Chrysostom, the second one, Basil the Great or Basil of Caesarea.

555
01:00:34,000 --> 01:00:38,000
 They lived in the 4th and 5th century.

556
01:00:38,000 --> 01:00:50,000
 Actually, some scholars think that both texts were written by John and Basil, but it's not sure.

557
01:00:50,000 --> 01:01:01,000
 Some scholars think that both texts were named because they came from their episcopal cities.

558
01:01:01,000 --> 01:01:08,000
 So, from Antioch of John Chrysostom and Caesarea from Caesarea Basil the Great.

559
01:01:08,000 --> 01:01:12,000
 What does it mean for Orthodox tradition?

560
01:01:12,000 --> 01:01:24,000
 This link or connection between theology, because Eucharistic prayer is always about theology.

561
01:01:24,000 --> 01:01:30,000
 It's very theological. It's addressed to the Father, to the Son, to the Holy Spirit.

562
01:01:30,000 --> 01:01:38,000
 It's a very theological work, but it is linked and deeply connected with concrete saints.

563
01:01:38,000 --> 01:01:44,000
 So, we don't imagine to pray with words by some unknown theologian.

564
01:01:44,000 --> 01:01:51,000
 We need some approach to a concrete human holiness.

565
01:01:51,000 --> 01:02:00,000
 If you ask me about St. Augustine and his possible contribution to Orthodox theology,

566
01:02:00,000 --> 01:02:03,000
 I think it's very important to speak about grace.

567
01:02:03,000 --> 01:02:14,000
 For sure, we use the word grace in Orthodox tradition, but the meaning is completely different.

568
01:02:14,000 --> 01:02:30,000
 For us, grace means ascetical work and results of this ascetical work in our personal life for perfection and holiness.

569
01:02:30,000 --> 01:02:36,000
 Grace is deeply connected with liturgical life and personal life and prayer,

570
01:02:36,000 --> 01:02:43,000
 but we don't know about the redemptive meaning of grace.

571
01:02:43,000 --> 01:02:54,000
 What is crucial, if we read St. Paul, is his understanding of the whole history of salvation.

572
01:02:54,000 --> 01:03:01,000
 Grace also means Jesus Christ given to us for the salvation of the whole world.

573
01:03:01,000 --> 01:03:07,000
 It also may be political theology because after Constantine the Great,

574
01:03:07,000 --> 01:03:17,000
 Eastern Christianity started being connected or linked with the Empire.

575
01:03:17,000 --> 01:03:27,000
 Why? Because many authors, but the most important was, I think, Eusebius of Caesarea.

576
01:03:27,000 --> 01:03:39,000
 He was quite sure that in this Christianization of biography of Constantine the Great,

577
01:03:39,000 --> 01:03:47,000
 his baptism on the dead bed and so on, was given a great blessing not only to the church,

578
01:03:47,000 --> 01:03:51,000
 but also to the history of the world.

579
01:03:51,000 --> 01:03:58,000
 And this hermeneutical approach goes on. It was never questioned.

580
01:03:58,000 --> 01:04:06,000
 And Augustine was outside of all those stories. Eusebius was very close to the Emperor.

581
01:04:06,000 --> 01:04:11,000
 He knew him personally. Augustine was in his native Africa.

582
01:04:11,000 --> 01:04:23,000
 He got 2,000 bishops at that time. And if we take a patriarch or a bishop of Caesarea as a basil,

583
01:04:23,000 --> 01:04:30,000
 they were very highly positioned. And Augustine was between first and second thousand of bishops.

584
01:04:30,000 --> 01:04:39,000
 And he didn't care about the Empire. For him, what was important was the salvation of his flock.

585
01:04:39,000 --> 01:04:48,000
 And that's why in his De Civitae Dei, he said, "It's okay. It's a very happy event that the Empire became Christian,

586
01:04:48,000 --> 01:04:56,000
 but one day maybe it will not be Christian anymore. We have to stay and to be Christian."

587
01:04:56,000 --> 01:05:07,000
 And I think we need this more skeptical approach in our own understanding of, I would call it, political theology.

588
01:05:07,000 --> 01:05:19,000
 And Augustine is, in this sense, among fathers. He is unique who could provide us such an answer. Thank you.

589
01:05:19,000 --> 01:05:27,000
 Thank you. So, Andrew, do you have any follow-up questions on this area?

590
01:05:35,000 --> 01:05:46,000
 Yes. Thank you for your response. It's very helpful to know that the fathers in Orthodoxy,

591
01:05:46,000 --> 01:05:53,000
 you have the idea of, like usually we think about patristic, we think about endpoints,

592
01:05:53,000 --> 01:06:00,000
 but you mentioned that the Church should, there should be fathers at all times.

593
01:06:00,000 --> 01:06:15,000
 So, I would like to follow up on this. I think the fathers' place in Orthodoxy is quite significant to the self-understanding of the Orthodox Church.

594
01:06:15,000 --> 01:06:33,000
 You mentioned that in the last century, there has been a few momentous historical events which impacted the Orthodox Church quite significantly.

595
01:06:33,000 --> 01:06:46,000
 You mentioned that the world was supposed to become Christian, but then all of a sudden, it had to fight for its own existence.

596
01:06:46,000 --> 01:07:00,000
 So, did these events in any way change the self-understanding of the Orthodox Christian, and also the way they think about the fathers?

597
01:07:00,000 --> 01:07:07,000
 That's my, that's a point I would like to follow up on.

598
01:07:07,000 --> 01:07:16,000
 I think that Orthodox understanding of the fathers became much more personalistic and ascetic.

599
01:07:16,000 --> 01:07:24,000
 So, first fathers were also, first of all, were teachers of dogmatics and true theologians.

600
01:07:24,000 --> 01:07:33,000
 After, they started being more personal saints in some kind.

601
01:07:33,000 --> 01:07:37,000
 It was a process of methodologization of fathers.

602
01:07:37,000 --> 01:07:45,000
 You mentioned also that St. Augustine is very different if you compare him to other fathers.

603
01:07:45,000 --> 01:07:49,000
 Why? Because his biography is very known.

604
01:07:49,000 --> 01:07:54,000
 Even some moments, we can restore it day by day.

605
01:07:54,000 --> 01:08:03,000
 But not only him is very known, but also if we read Gregory of Nazianzus, he is very personal.

606
01:08:03,000 --> 01:08:15,000
 Sometimes he is happy, he calls, "Oh, my Trinity, I'm happy defending my Orthodox faith in Constantinople."

607
01:08:15,000 --> 01:08:27,000
 Sometimes he is very depressive and he quotes Greek ancient pagan authors and he forgets about his theological roots.

608
01:08:27,000 --> 01:08:42,000
 I think Orthodox people, after this huge reform, I would say, after the arrival of Islam,

609
01:08:42,000 --> 01:08:53,000
 they start rethinking the role of the fathers and they start also forgetting about their personal dimension.

610
01:08:53,000 --> 01:09:03,000
 Fathers became figures on the firmament of the Orthodox faith,

611
01:09:03,000 --> 01:09:17,000
 but not concrete personalities who needed also analysis and also chronology, biography, personal approach.

612
01:09:17,000 --> 01:09:29,000
 I think this revival of the patristic theology was also due to the fact that even if the Orthodox world was very separated from the rest of the world,

613
01:09:29,000 --> 01:09:35,000
 academic theology, especially in the Russian Empire, was very high level.

614
01:09:35,000 --> 01:09:43,000
 I don't know if you know, but even theological teaching was given in Latin language.

615
01:09:43,000 --> 01:09:54,000
 Imagine people praying Church Slavonics, speaking Russian dialects, you have la noblesse, nobility in Russian Empire, speaking French,

616
01:09:54,000 --> 01:10:01,000
 and priests and theologians doing theology in Latin language.

617
01:10:01,000 --> 01:10:11,000
 It means that theological educational parkour was the same as in the West, but contents were different.

618
01:10:11,000 --> 01:10:18,000
 It was so difficult to understand that nobody cared about it.

619
01:10:18,000 --> 01:10:28,000
 I think this discovery of the fathers in the 20th century was very important because we finally started studying ourselves

620
01:10:28,000 --> 01:10:30,000
 and understand that we are different.

621
01:10:30,000 --> 01:10:36,000
 It's not bad or good, but difference is a gift given by God.

622
01:10:36,000 --> 01:10:43,000
 I think that was the most important meaning of the patristic revival in the 20th century.

623
01:10:43,000 --> 01:11:07,000
 So, from your original script, I have read some message from your speech that the Orthodox tradition has skipped some historical moments,

624
01:11:07,000 --> 01:11:20,000
 which is very important to the Western tradition, like the Renaissance, Reformation, Enlightenment, and all these important historical moments.

625
01:11:20,000 --> 01:11:30,000
 So, do you think this is a theological pro or a theological con for the Orthodox tradition?

626
01:11:30,000 --> 01:11:47,000
 For many who become Orthodox in our time, it's a huge pro because you have a church which didn't compromise itself with today's world.

627
01:11:47,000 --> 01:12:00,000
 Also, in history, it's very easy to be Orthodox and if you hear inquisition, no idea, persecution of heretics, we didn't do it, and so on.

628
01:12:00,000 --> 01:12:12,000
 But when people are already Orthodox, they start questioning about philosophical issues, how to deal with the Reformation,

629
01:12:12,000 --> 01:12:27,000
 with all those immense themes and topics and challenges we live, we don't always have appropriate questions because we didn't have this experience.

630
01:12:27,000 --> 01:12:36,000
 That's why I think a communicable dialogue is so important, because we can enrich each other and learn from each other.

631
01:12:36,000 --> 01:12:50,000
 We cannot in a moment leave all those things we didn't leave, like Enlightenment, Renaissance, Reformation, modernity, maybe post-modernity,

632
01:12:50,000 --> 01:12:58,000
 but let's leave it together in order not to repeat our errors before.

633
01:13:03,000 --> 01:13:09,000
 Well, we are coming from evangelical tradition, so Protestant, basically.

634
01:13:09,000 --> 01:13:17,000
 So for the Protestant tradition, the scripture is very important. We have scripture principles, sola scriptura.

635
01:13:17,000 --> 01:13:27,000
 So compared with the Orthodox Church, it seems to me that the church fathers is very important to your tradition.

636
01:13:27,000 --> 01:13:37,000
 So in your opinion, or in your observation, what is the place of scripture in the Orthodox tradition compared with the church fathers?

637
01:13:37,000 --> 01:13:48,000
 It's a very important question. As I teach in theological academy, seminary, dogmatics,

638
01:13:48,000 --> 01:14:01,000
 one of my first questions was, did somebody read the whole Bible? And almost nobody answered yes.

639
01:14:01,000 --> 01:14:13,000
 Also, second question, do you read sometimes the fathers? And whom do they quote? Each other or their predecessors?

640
01:14:13,000 --> 01:14:21,000
 No. Usually, all their spirituality, theology is in the Bible.

641
01:14:21,000 --> 01:14:29,000
 They knew that by heart. The question of how did they interpret it is a different question.

642
01:14:29,000 --> 01:14:36,000
 But anyway, all the fathers were deeply rooted in the scripture.

643
01:14:36,000 --> 01:14:45,000
 And I think in our Orthodox tradition, it's a huge lack of this immediate approach to the Bible.

644
01:14:45,000 --> 01:14:54,000
 We have to read and to re-read it. And still, maybe we lived already a liturgical revival, a patristical revival.

645
01:14:54,000 --> 01:15:00,000
 Maybe let's now start with biblical revival. I think it's important.

646
01:15:00,000 --> 01:15:07,000
 So do you expect an Orthodox version of Martin Luther coming up?

647
01:15:07,000 --> 01:15:18,000
 Martin Luther was too Augustinian. First we have to study Augustine and then...

648
01:15:18,000 --> 01:15:25,000
 Okay, Andrews, do you have other questions for Dr. Zukolowski?

649
01:15:25,000 --> 01:15:31,000
 Yeah, I think I have one more question. I know your interest is in ecumenism.

650
01:15:31,000 --> 01:15:38,000
 And so I would like to hear more about the work that you have been doing.

651
01:15:38,000 --> 01:15:52,000
 Do you see ecumenism as primarily something that can be fulfilled academically or through dialogue?

652
01:15:52,000 --> 01:15:59,000
 It's a topic that interested me and I think it's a very important subject too.

653
01:15:59,000 --> 01:16:06,000
 The fact that we are having dialogue here, I think, is part of the effort towards Christian union.

654
01:16:06,000 --> 01:16:12,000
 So I would like to hear you share about your expertise.

655
01:16:12,000 --> 01:16:22,000
 I think we are in a very difficult situation because the ecumenical movement started in the beginning of the 20th century.

656
01:16:22,000 --> 01:16:28,000
 It has become very disappointed and weak.

657
01:16:28,000 --> 01:16:34,000
 And all those great hopes are not actual anymore.

658
01:16:34,000 --> 01:16:43,000
 Why different answers? Maybe because we were in modernity, now in post-modernity.

659
01:16:43,000 --> 01:16:46,000
 Maybe difference become too important.

660
01:16:46,000 --> 01:16:52,000
 Maybe theological and philosophical dimensions also not so important.

661
01:16:52,000 --> 01:17:00,000
 We have to be in aesthetics and also huge political issue about what we are.

662
01:17:00,000 --> 01:17:06,000
 Is it not better to be separated than to be united?

663
01:17:06,000 --> 01:17:09,000
 There is no quest for unity anymore.

664
01:17:09,000 --> 01:17:19,000
 And I think it also has its repercussions for the ecumenical movement.

665
01:17:19,000 --> 01:17:27,000
 The best example of ecumenism in my personal experience was when I was in a conference in Singapore.

666
01:17:27,000 --> 01:17:33,000
 I didn't know that it was a huge conference.

667
01:17:33,000 --> 01:17:39,000
 I was sent by Fribourg and I was sure I will meet some Catholics, Orthodox, Protestants.

668
01:17:39,000 --> 01:17:44,000
 But I was almost alone in a huge Protestant congregation.

669
01:17:44,000 --> 01:17:49,000
 And people I discussed with were Russian Baptists.

670
01:17:49,000 --> 01:17:55,000
 They are very conservative, very true Baptists.

671
01:17:55,000 --> 01:18:06,000
 But I discovered that they didn't know at that time enough about their classical Baptist theology.

672
01:18:06,000 --> 01:18:14,000
 And I asked, "What do you mean about Trinity, about redemption, grace, baptism?"

673
01:18:14,000 --> 01:18:19,000
 And answers in my understanding were not enough good.

674
01:18:19,000 --> 01:18:29,000
 So I said, "Guys, you are Baptists. You were born from heaven in your tradition.

675
01:18:29,000 --> 01:18:39,000
 Probably you will be always Baptists until you are in heaven where there is no confession in the sense of denomination.

676
01:18:39,000 --> 01:18:47,000
 Let me please teach you a little bit about the Johan doctrine."

677
01:18:47,000 --> 01:18:58,000
 And I also want other Christians to teach me about the Orthodox faith, tradition, understanding.

678
01:18:58,000 --> 01:19:06,000
 And what actually I noticed also studying in a different context in Fribourg,

679
01:19:06,000 --> 01:19:15,000
 that I learned a lot about my own tradition from non-Orthodox people, Catholics, Protestants.

680
01:19:15,000 --> 01:19:21,000
 The best way to pray I learned from some Protestant Christians.

681
01:19:21,000 --> 01:19:27,000
 I mean the best way in the sense of being able to pronounce the word of prayer immediately.

682
01:19:27,000 --> 01:19:31,000
 You know, immediately, this immediate way of addressing God.

683
01:19:31,000 --> 01:19:38,000
 And I think maybe it's one of the possibilities or hopes for a future ecumenical dialogue,

684
01:19:38,000 --> 01:19:45,000
 to share experiences of each other and to understand that we are not perfect.

685
01:19:45,000 --> 01:19:57,000
 Let's think about our roots and also go towards the future because Christians in the world are now in minority.

686
01:19:57,000 --> 01:20:05,000
 Even in statistics maybe not, but Christian faith was never about statistics.

687
01:20:05,000 --> 01:20:23,000
 And let's go very small flock towards a true ecumenical dialogue where we are all different but all together.

688
01:20:23,000 --> 01:20:32,000
 Okay, so I think we are now opening the floor to the Q&A session.

689
01:20:32,000 --> 01:20:39,000
 So you are most welcome to raise your question to two of our speakers.

690
01:20:39,000 --> 01:20:50,000
 So if you have any questions, please come forward and use the mic in the middle of our room.

691
01:20:50,000 --> 01:21:01,000
 And for the sake of time, each one, please raise one question and finish it within a minute.

692
01:21:01,000 --> 01:21:18,000
 So we can now start.

693
01:21:18,000 --> 01:21:22,000
 Hello, my name is Keen. I teach church history here.

694
01:21:22,000 --> 01:21:27,000
 So just broadening your scope a little bit.

695
01:21:27,000 --> 01:21:33,000
 First, I'd like to thank you. You are so humble in presenting the Orthodox tradition.

696
01:21:33,000 --> 01:21:38,000
 I find that sometimes it's not true in some other Orthodox writers.

697
01:21:38,000 --> 01:21:40,000
 So very good.

698
01:21:40,000 --> 01:21:43,000
 Secondly, just that's my question.

699
01:21:43,000 --> 01:21:52,000
 Actually, in terms of purely population statistics, the Orthodox tradition is in a pretty bad situation.

700
01:21:52,000 --> 01:21:57,000
 Russians, Eastern Europeans, they are not reproducing children.

701
01:21:57,000 --> 01:22:08,000
 So my question is that in the Orthodox community, do they have a sense like how the church can survive,

702
01:22:08,000 --> 01:22:15,000
 the Orthodox church can survive both the decline of the church and the attack of modernity and so forth and so on.

703
01:22:15,000 --> 01:22:33,000
 Do they have a sense of crisis facing the church or do they have any discussion how to face the problem of the Orthodox community at large today?

704
01:22:33,000 --> 01:22:44,000
 First of all, Orthodoxy is not anymore Orthodoxy in a definite country or somewhere on earth.

705
01:22:44,000 --> 01:22:51,000
 But you have everywhere Orthodox communities in the diaspora.

706
01:22:51,000 --> 01:22:58,000
 And actually, we speak about 14 Orthodox churches which are independent.

707
01:22:58,000 --> 01:23:06,000
 And if you compare it, it's more or less the model of the Anglican communion.

708
01:23:06,000 --> 01:23:19,000
 It's not, it wasn't a project, but it's going this direction, being a kind of confederation of churches.

709
01:23:19,000 --> 01:23:31,000
 And you have to speak about each tradition differently because in different countries you have different situations.

710
01:23:31,000 --> 01:23:44,000
 But I think that we lived the time of persecution during the Soviet past and we were so happy that it ended

711
01:23:44,000 --> 01:23:51,000
 that we still not questioned ourselves what will come in the future.

712
01:23:51,000 --> 01:24:06,000
 And Orthodoxy has a very strong identity with culture, ethnicity, history, particular history of its own land, country.

713
01:24:06,000 --> 01:24:15,000
 If you want to compare, it's a little bit like Polish Catholicism.

714
01:24:15,000 --> 01:24:23,000
 You know, everybody was happy with a lot of people in churches during the Soviet time.

715
01:24:23,000 --> 01:24:33,000
 Then John Paul II was the greatest Polish of all times.

716
01:24:33,000 --> 01:24:40,000
 Now everything changed, but Polish Catholics are still inside this reality.

717
01:24:40,000 --> 01:24:44,000
 I think it's more or less that answer.

718
01:24:44,000 --> 01:24:55,000
 But you have also Orthodoxy in the United States, in South America, you have in South Africa,

719
01:24:55,000 --> 01:25:08,000
 strong Greek community, they are more aware of all these challenges we face or we will face.

720
01:25:08,000 --> 01:25:12,000
 I think the answer is yes and not.

721
01:25:12,000 --> 01:25:23,000
 But not in such a, you know, if you compare with the West, with Catholics or Protestants,

722
01:25:23,000 --> 01:25:45,000
 we are still not aware yet of all those new challenges we will face in the coming future.

723
01:25:45,000 --> 01:25:49,000
 My name is Cherry. I'm also a church historian.

724
01:25:49,000 --> 01:25:56,000
 And thank you so much for Father Sokolowsky's presentation and Andrew's response,

725
01:25:56,000 --> 01:26:04,000
 which are both very helpful for us who all claim ourselves as the descendants of the Latin tradition,

726
01:26:04,000 --> 01:26:10,000
 while we're having mostly Asian faces, ethically.

727
01:26:10,000 --> 01:26:20,000
 But this is a great opportunity for all of us to learn about how the Orthodox community has been receiving Augustine's teaching.

728
01:26:20,000 --> 01:26:28,000
 I actually had three questions.

729
01:26:28,000 --> 01:26:33,000
 I'm trying to combine two of them.

730
01:26:33,000 --> 01:26:48,000
 So did Father Sokolowsky, do you notice any similar negation occurred in some other church fathers

731
01:26:48,000 --> 01:26:58,000
 considered as Latin fathers, such as Amboise, Jerome, and perhaps a little bit later, Gregory the Great,

732
01:26:58,000 --> 01:27:04,000
 which is related to this question, is that,

733
01:27:04,000 --> 01:27:14,000
 do you believe that the primary obstacles in introducing Augustine's teaching in the Orthodox community

734
01:27:14,000 --> 01:27:24,000
 is the lack of sainthood or do controversial theological differences play a more significant role?

735
01:27:24,000 --> 01:27:33,000
 So what I mean is that because Amboise, Jerome, and perhaps Gregory the Great are the fathers

736
01:27:33,000 --> 01:27:44,000
 who did not engage in the controversy of filioque, but Augustine was a very significant one.

737
01:27:44,000 --> 01:27:54,000
 Did this actually hinder the popularity of Augustine's teaching a lot in the Orthodox church?

738
01:27:54,000 --> 01:27:56,000
 This is my question, thank you.

739
01:27:56,000 --> 01:28:03,000
 Okay, thank you. First question, I would point to St Cyprian of Carthage.

740
01:28:03,000 --> 01:28:08,000
 You know that Gregory, he wasn't known in the East,

741
01:28:08,000 --> 01:28:14,000
 but his teaching on sacraments outside the church and salvation outside the church

742
01:28:14,000 --> 01:28:18,000
 was very important for all Latin tradition.

743
01:28:18,000 --> 01:28:26,000
 And what he was saying was that he didn't actually recognize sacraments outside the church.

744
01:28:26,000 --> 01:28:31,000
 How did he practically respond to it, we don't know.

745
01:28:31,000 --> 01:28:37,000
 But it was a very hard position, and St Augustine corrected it.

746
01:28:37,000 --> 01:28:47,000
 And after, more or less, in the ancient tradition, we don't have a practice of,

747
01:28:47,000 --> 01:28:56,000
 you know, don't recognize sacraments as such, but he wasn't known in the East

748
01:28:56,000 --> 01:29:02,000
 because St Gregory, not only because of St Gregory, but Gregory of Nazianzus

749
01:29:02,000 --> 01:29:09,000
 confused him with another theologian, not theologian, but bishop called Cyprian of Antioch.

750
01:29:09,000 --> 01:29:15,000
 And Cyprian of Antioch was a magician who converted to Christian faith

751
01:29:15,000 --> 01:29:17,000
 and produced a lot of miracles.

752
01:29:17,000 --> 01:29:27,000
 So they confused him, and that's why his theology was not studied and accepted

753
01:29:27,000 --> 01:29:31,000
 and had no reception.

754
01:29:31,000 --> 01:29:37,000
 And in the beginning of the 20th century, one of the Russian theologians

755
01:29:37,000 --> 01:29:46,000
 adopted this teaching of St Cyprian, Hilarion, bishop Hilarion,

756
01:29:46,000 --> 01:29:52,000
 not our contemporary, but another one, and applied it to the ecumenical movement,

757
01:29:52,000 --> 01:29:59,000
 saying that outside the church there is no salvation, let's stop every ecumenism.

758
01:29:59,000 --> 01:30:06,000
 One of the examples of how other fathers were received in today's Orthodoxy,

759
01:30:06,000 --> 01:30:12,000
 you spoke about Ambrose and Jerome and Gregory the Great.

760
01:30:12,000 --> 01:30:16,000
 I'm not sure that it's because of the filioque.

761
01:30:16,000 --> 01:30:25,000
 I think that they lived in an area which was much more close to the Eastern Christianity

762
01:30:25,000 --> 01:30:33,000
 because Ambrose was in Milano and the empire was still more or less united.

763
01:30:33,000 --> 01:30:40,000
 That's why he was known and he also criticized harshly the emperor Theodosius

764
01:30:40,000 --> 01:30:44,000
 who was after the emperor in Constantinople.

765
01:30:44,000 --> 01:30:47,000
 So they knew each other very good.

766
01:30:47,000 --> 01:30:53,000
 Also you have Gregory the Great who was an ambassador in Constantinople

767
01:30:53,000 --> 01:30:55,000
 before he became Pope.

768
01:30:55,000 --> 01:31:02,000
 And Jerome, he moved to Palestine, so he involved himself in a lot of controversies

769
01:31:02,000 --> 01:31:06,000
 of that time which were very actual for the East.

770
01:31:06,000 --> 01:31:10,000
 And Augustine was in Carthago.

771
01:31:10,000 --> 01:31:16,000
 This church didn't exist anymore since the 7th century.

772
01:31:16,000 --> 01:31:22,000
 So virtually he was one of the Western Latin fathers,

773
01:31:22,000 --> 01:31:27,000
 but in reality he belonged to a generation already lost.

774
01:31:27,000 --> 01:31:36,000
 All this huge tradition started with Tertullian to Hermian of Facunda

775
01:31:36,000 --> 01:31:41,000
 and Fulgencius of Ruspe ended.

776
01:31:41,000 --> 01:31:49,000
 And it's a great luck that we have almost all the works of St. Augustine preserved,

777
01:31:49,000 --> 01:31:52,000
 but his tradition was lost.

778
01:31:52,000 --> 01:31:59,000
 That's why he was too far away from the Orthodox tradition, I think.

779
01:32:10,000 --> 01:32:13,000
 Any other questions?

780
01:32:13,000 --> 01:32:22,000
 In your lecture you have mentioned that in the 18th century

781
01:32:22,000 --> 01:32:27,000
 there is a, how to say, a breakthrough.

782
01:32:27,000 --> 01:32:33,000
 Nicodemus, the reformer of the liturgical calendar,

783
01:32:33,000 --> 01:32:39,000
 he added the name of Augustine and Jerome into the liturgical calendar.

784
01:32:39,000 --> 01:32:44,000
 So what's the motivation behind this ad,

785
01:32:44,000 --> 01:32:49,000
 I mean, addition of the name of a Latin father?

786
01:32:49,000 --> 01:32:55,000
 There were very few signs in our calendar

787
01:32:55,000 --> 01:32:59,000
 and many great saints were not in.

788
01:32:59,000 --> 01:33:03,000
 That was his first motivation.

789
01:33:03,000 --> 01:33:10,000
 He also lived in, actually we say Greece, but it was not Greece,

790
01:33:10,000 --> 01:33:14,000
 it was future Greece, Greek Republic, Hellenic Republic,

791
01:33:14,000 --> 01:33:18,000
 where population were mixed.

792
01:33:18,000 --> 01:33:23,000
 You have a lot of Turkish people, Muslim people, Christian people,

793
01:33:23,000 --> 01:33:30,000
 and I think for him the purpose was to educate people through the calendar

794
01:33:30,000 --> 01:33:38,000
 because theology, it wasn't yet the independent state of Greece,

795
01:33:38,000 --> 01:33:43,000
 that's why theologians, there were no theological schools or faculties,

796
01:33:43,000 --> 01:33:45,000
 only for small children.

797
01:33:45,000 --> 01:33:49,000
 And he wanted through this liturgical, all day,

798
01:33:49,000 --> 01:33:54,000
 to educate people to go deeper to the roots.

799
01:33:54,000 --> 01:34:01,000
 Also, when he spoke about frequent communion, he was criticized,

800
01:34:01,000 --> 01:34:07,000
 and people, his adversaries, they said,

801
01:34:07,000 --> 01:34:15,000
 "Nicodemus is taking with him always in pocket Eucharist, he is a magician."

802
01:34:15,000 --> 01:34:17,000
 And what does it mean?

803
01:34:17,000 --> 01:34:23,000
 It means that people criticizing him were very obscurantist,

804
01:34:23,000 --> 01:34:25,000
 but also not educated enough.

805
01:34:25,000 --> 01:34:34,000
 And I think it was a kind of enlightenment in Christian sense of word

806
01:34:34,000 --> 01:34:39,000
 to bring to his own people, I think so.

807
01:34:39,000 --> 01:34:42,000
 But why Augustine?

808
01:34:42,000 --> 01:34:44,000
 Because he wasn't in the calendar.

809
01:34:44,000 --> 01:34:48,000
 [laughter]

810
01:34:48,000 --> 01:34:56,000
 You have also some fathers very important for the Orthodox tradition,

811
01:34:56,000 --> 01:35:02,000
 as Evagrius from Egypt, you have also Theodoret of Cyrus,

812
01:35:02,000 --> 01:35:07,000
 but they are more problematic because they got formal condemnation

813
01:35:07,000 --> 01:35:15,000
 by some ecumenical councils, and I spoke about church of the fathers,

814
01:35:15,000 --> 01:35:16,000
 that's one definition.

815
01:35:16,000 --> 01:35:22,000
 Another definition of the Orthodoxy formulated in the 20th century

816
01:35:22,000 --> 01:35:27,000
 was church of the seven ecumenical councils, also very important.

817
01:35:27,000 --> 01:35:31,000
 That's why Augustine didn't participate in any council,

818
01:35:31,000 --> 01:35:35,000
 that's why he remained unknown for the most Orthodox.

819
01:35:35,000 --> 01:35:41,000
 And those fathers I mentioned, they did not participate,

820
01:35:41,000 --> 01:35:43,000
 but they were condemned by the councils.

821
01:35:43,000 --> 01:35:47,000
 That's why he could not put them in the calendar.

822
01:35:47,000 --> 01:35:58,000
 So the second question for Tim.

823
01:35:58,000 --> 01:36:02,000
 You know, for us Protestants, you know we are a Protestant church,

824
01:36:02,000 --> 01:36:08,000
 our church fathers is Calvin and Luther and the Anabaptists and so forth.

825
01:36:08,000 --> 01:36:15,000
 So I just wonder for the Orthodox tradition, do people actually discuss Calvin and Luther?

826
01:36:15,000 --> 01:36:21,000
 How much they know about this reformer, hero, our church fathers, so called?

827
01:36:21,000 --> 01:36:29,000
 We have still comparative theology in our theological faculties,

828
01:36:29,000 --> 01:36:38,000
 and there we study Roman Catholic dogma and also Protestant tradition.

829
01:36:38,000 --> 01:36:46,000
 And we are very critical towards the Roman Catholics

830
01:36:46,000 --> 01:36:49,000
 and very sympathetic towards Protestants,

831
01:36:49,000 --> 01:36:56,000
 because we say they were our friends but they didn't know about us.

832
01:36:56,000 --> 01:36:59,000
 [laughter]

833
01:36:59,000 --> 01:37:11,000
 But unfortunately we didn't go to some concrete theological problematics

834
01:37:11,000 --> 01:37:17,000
 of that time of Martin Luther, Jean Calvin, which were very important,

835
01:37:17,000 --> 01:37:20,000
 very interesting also.

836
01:37:20,000 --> 01:37:26,000
 Once I spoke to a Lutheran theologian, Christoph Felmy from Germany,

837
01:37:26,000 --> 01:37:32,000
 and I just shared some theological views, and he said,

838
01:37:32,000 --> 01:37:38,000
 "You are like Martin Luther in your theology, but you are not Lutheran. That's good."

839
01:37:38,000 --> 01:37:40,000
 [laughter]

840
01:37:40,000 --> 01:37:44,000
 "And you know also about Lutheran Orthodoxy."

841
01:37:44,000 --> 01:37:47,000
 [silence]

842
01:37:48,000 --> 01:37:49,000
 [thud]

843
01:37:49,000 --> 01:38:17,000
 [silence]

844
01:38:17,000 --> 01:38:21,000
 So we have Old Testament question, right?

845
01:38:21,000 --> 01:38:23,000
 There's a long way to walk.

846
01:38:23,000 --> 01:38:27,000
 Thank you, Father.

847
01:38:27,000 --> 01:38:37,000
 You brought us a fresh perspective that Augustine was a heretic,

848
01:38:37,000 --> 01:38:44,000
 according to the Eastern Orthodox tradition, which is refreshing.

849
01:38:44,000 --> 01:38:51,000
 Because I'm interested in this different perspective,

850
01:38:51,000 --> 01:38:56,000
 as it has been very difficult for me this evening,

851
01:38:56,000 --> 01:39:02,000
 imagining someone from Switzerland representing the East,

852
01:39:02,000 --> 01:39:08,000
 whereas a Chinese young theologian from Hong Kong coming back from Oxford

853
01:39:08,000 --> 01:39:10,000
 representing the West.

854
01:39:10,000 --> 01:39:14,000
 It's paradoxical, but it's true.

855
01:39:14,000 --> 01:39:22,000
 Different perspectives no longer divided by ethnicity, background.

856
01:39:22,000 --> 01:39:30,000
 Say for Chinese Church, if the Nestorian missionary back in the 7th century

857
01:39:30,000 --> 01:39:33,000
 was successful enough,

858
01:39:33,000 --> 01:39:41,000
 then we would be under the Eastern Orthodox tradition rather than the West missionary movement.

859
01:39:41,000 --> 01:39:49,000
 You mentioned that Augustine was called "Blessed" rather than "Saint" Augustine.

860
01:39:49,000 --> 01:39:57,000
 Virgin Mary is called "Blessed," not "Saint."

861
01:39:57,000 --> 01:40:07,000
 Does it imply any hierarchical order, or was it just a difference in language?

862
01:40:07,000 --> 01:40:13,000
 I noticed from your three definitions of Eastern Orthodoxy,

863
01:40:13,000 --> 01:40:21,000
 you did not include the word "Greek" in either of your three definitions.

864
01:40:21,000 --> 01:40:25,000
 And you mentioned "Greek" quite later on.

865
01:40:25,000 --> 01:40:30,000
 But according to our education from the West,

866
01:40:30,000 --> 01:40:35,000
 they were the Greek fathers and the Latin fathers.

867
01:40:35,000 --> 01:40:41,000
 Augustine apparently did not know any Greek or Hebrew.

868
01:40:41,000 --> 01:40:44,000
 He was the Latin father.

869
01:40:44,000 --> 01:40:54,000
 Was it because of language that he was misunderstood or categorized as a heretic?

870
01:40:54,000 --> 01:40:58,000
 Was it language that is dividing the Church?

871
01:40:58,000 --> 01:41:02,000
 Or was it, as you said, political, historical?

872
01:41:02,000 --> 01:41:09,000
 I noticed that this evening we have an ecumenical language, which is English.

873
01:41:09,000 --> 01:41:13,000
 It is no longer Latin in the West, in Europe.

874
01:41:13,000 --> 01:41:16,000
 It's not German, but now it's English.

875
01:41:16,000 --> 01:41:21,000
 And what about the 22nd century? Would it be Chinese?

876
01:41:21,000 --> 01:41:31,000
 The number of Christians from mainland China will overtake all the other communities.

877
01:41:31,000 --> 01:41:42,000
 What would you say about this issue of language from history, and also looking into the future?

878
01:41:42,000 --> 01:41:46,000
 Please.

879
01:41:46,000 --> 01:41:53,000
 That's interesting that we call all the Oriental fathers "Greek fathers," but they weren't Greek.

880
01:41:53,000 --> 01:41:59,000
 And we know now more than we knew before.

881
01:41:59,000 --> 01:42:05,000
 And Teodorato of Cyrus, I mentioned, he was a Syriac father.

882
01:42:05,000 --> 01:42:11,000
 And John Chrysostom lived a huge Syriac experience.

883
01:42:11,000 --> 01:42:18,000
 And one of the greatest fathers of the East was Meletius of Antioch.

884
01:42:18,000 --> 01:42:24,000
 He sent Gregory of Nazianzus to Constantinople to preach on Trinity.

885
01:42:24,000 --> 01:42:27,000
 He sent Basil the Great.

886
01:42:27,000 --> 01:42:32,000
 Basil wanted to be ascetical, and he sent him to be bishop.

887
01:42:32,000 --> 01:42:37,000
 And he also ordained John Chrysostom.

888
01:42:37,000 --> 01:42:42,000
 But he unfortunately died during the Second Ecumenical Council of 381.

889
01:42:42,000 --> 01:42:45,000
 But he was Armenian.

890
01:42:45,000 --> 01:42:53,000
 And I think we have to discover this multiplicity of the ancient church.

891
01:42:53,000 --> 01:43:03,000
 And I think there is something very imperialistic in this logic of Greek or Latin, Latin or Greek.

892
01:43:03,000 --> 01:43:12,000
 And I think the problem is that Latins, they usually knew about Greek fathers.

893
01:43:12,000 --> 01:43:17,000
 And Greek fathers didn't read Latin fathers.

894
01:43:17,000 --> 01:43:25,000
 The first translations of the Trinitate of Augustine, this famous work,

895
01:43:25,000 --> 01:43:31,000
 which is actually, you cannot understand Philioque without having read this work,

896
01:43:31,000 --> 01:43:37,000
 it was first translated in the 13th century in Constantinople.

897
01:43:37,000 --> 01:43:46,000
 And many details like this, I'm unhappy with.

898
01:43:46,000 --> 01:43:59,000
 I think that also German and French and Italian and Spanish and in future

899
01:43:59,000 --> 01:44:08,000
 many other languages will become more and more Christian and important for theology, I think.

900
01:44:08,000 --> 01:44:13,000
 Not only English, because language is also a question of thinking.

901
01:44:13,000 --> 01:44:16,000
 And we all think differently.

902
01:44:16,000 --> 01:44:19,000
 And if you impose one language to everybody,

903
01:44:19,000 --> 01:44:30,000
 you impose your own rules of some internal hermeneutic you even don't see and don't get it immediately.

904
01:44:30,000 --> 01:44:36,000
 And that's why also I think St. Augustine was not understood enough,

905
01:44:36,000 --> 01:44:38,000
 because he thought differently.

906
01:44:38,000 --> 01:44:43,000
 And many Orthodox theologians in the 19th century,

907
01:44:43,000 --> 01:44:49,000
 they discovered Augustine in an academic way, not in a theological way.

908
01:44:49,000 --> 01:45:04,000
 And they were noticing that Augustine got a lot of lacks in his thinking.

909
01:45:04,000 --> 01:45:11,000
 For instance, he identifies Platonism and Plato and Aristotle.

910
01:45:11,000 --> 01:45:19,000
 For him, new Platonism is only Platonic philosophy developed.

911
01:45:19,000 --> 01:45:22,000
 In Christian theology, even more.

912
01:45:22,000 --> 01:45:27,000
 Now some scholars think that he didn't know Greek, but he didn't want to put it ahead.

913
01:45:27,000 --> 01:45:35,000
 What is important is that now we are a little bit different compared to modernity.

914
01:45:35,000 --> 01:45:41,000
 And we know that not knowing about something is not always bad.

915
01:45:41,000 --> 01:45:50,000
 That's why Augustine could develop his own theology without knowing Greek theology.

916
01:45:50,000 --> 01:45:57,000
 That's why it's so amazing, sometimes very paradoxical, very tragical, but different.

917
01:45:57,000 --> 01:46:09,000
 And that's a very interesting story, what would happen if Nestorian missionaries came to China at that time.

918
01:46:09,000 --> 01:46:17,000
 But it's also a very interesting question, because it's linked with all political developments of that time.

919
01:46:17,000 --> 01:46:22,000
 You know that the Roman Empire became Orthodox,

920
01:46:22,000 --> 01:46:30,000
 and all Christians outside of it had to disappear because they were in some way adhering to the Roman faith.

921
01:46:30,000 --> 01:46:37,000
 Or to become different, to become monophysites or Nestorians or something like this.

922
01:46:37,000 --> 01:46:47,000
 And I think this question of Augustine is also linked with the coronation of Charlemagne in the year 800,

923
01:46:47,000 --> 01:46:52,000
 when he proclaimed himself the emperor.

924
01:46:52,000 --> 01:47:03,000
 At that time, they did believe in one God, one Jesus Christ, one scripture, one Caesar.

925
01:47:03,000 --> 01:47:09,000
 And that was a huge challenge to the imperial church in Constantinople.

926
01:47:09,000 --> 01:47:16,000
 That's why they started also distancing themselves from the Latin tradition.

927
01:47:16,000 --> 01:47:24,000
 And you have this coronation of Charlemagne and Fortius of Constantinople,

928
01:47:24,000 --> 01:47:33,000
 almost at the same time simultaneously polemics arose between Greek and Latin Christianity.

929
01:47:41,000 --> 01:47:53,000
 So from language, any related question about language, culture, from the missionary perspective?

930
01:47:53,000 --> 01:47:56,000
 Anyway, I'm not forcing you.

931
01:47:56,000 --> 01:48:00,000
 Okay, any other questions?

932
01:48:00,000 --> 01:48:08,000
 I have a rather practical question this time.

933
01:48:08,000 --> 01:48:19,000
 It's about whether it's easier for people like you to promote Augustine's work in countries or areas

934
01:48:19,000 --> 01:48:23,000
 which is outside the former Byzantine areas.

935
01:48:23,000 --> 01:48:29,000
 Because I noticed that in your presentation, you mentioned a lot about different theologians doing the same work.

936
01:48:29,000 --> 01:48:38,000
 But most of them work in areas like in Europe, like yourself, and also in the United States.

937
01:48:38,000 --> 01:48:50,000
 So I wonder, is it difficult, maybe more difficult for you to promote Augustine's work in eastern,

938
01:48:50,000 --> 01:48:54,000
 the former historically eastern countries?

939
01:48:54,000 --> 01:48:57,000
 Or is it more or less the same?

940
01:48:57,000 --> 01:48:59,000
 This is my question. Thank you.

941
01:48:59,000 --> 01:49:09,000
 In some way, yes, because there is a cliche that St. Augustine was a teacher of,

942
01:49:09,000 --> 01:49:12,000
 or an example of Christian penitence.

943
01:49:12,000 --> 01:49:18,000
 And the focus is on his biography.

944
01:49:18,000 --> 01:49:20,000
 He was not Christian.

945
01:49:20,000 --> 01:49:30,000
 He was a heretic before, he adhered to Manichaeism, after he was baptized by St. Ambrose, and that's all.

946
01:49:30,000 --> 01:49:37,000
 Why? Because orthodoxy is focused on asceticism.

947
01:49:37,000 --> 01:49:38,000
 It's enough.

948
01:49:38,000 --> 01:49:46,000
 It's very hard, very difficult to combine theology, dogmatics, and ascetics

949
01:49:46,000 --> 01:49:50,000
 lived in such a way.

950
01:49:50,000 --> 01:49:58,000
 And also, it's very good to speak about yourself, Church of the Fathers,

951
01:49:58,000 --> 01:50:00,000
 but you need to study Fathers.

952
01:50:00,000 --> 01:50:08,000
 But if you already called yourself Church of the Fathers, you don't study the Fathers, usually like this.

953
01:50:08,000 --> 01:50:12,000
 That's why it's very difficult to speak about St. Augustine,

954
01:50:12,000 --> 01:50:18,000
 because everybody thinks that we know about him, everything.

955
01:50:18,000 --> 01:50:23,000
 In the Western or Eastern context, outside orthodox countries,

956
01:50:23,000 --> 01:50:30,000
 it's easier because you share your opinion and we are open for every kind of discussion.

957
01:50:30,000 --> 01:50:38,000
 Any other questions?

958
01:50:38,000 --> 01:50:49,000
 I know nothing about Augustine, and I know nothing about the Church history,

959
01:50:49,000 --> 01:50:52,000
 but I know something about Psalms.

960
01:50:52,000 --> 01:51:00,000
 My question would be, what is the position of reciting the Psalms in the Orthodox liturgy?

961
01:51:00,000 --> 01:51:14,000
 How would that recitation be a way to form the piety and also the spirituality of the Orthodox believers?

962
01:51:14,000 --> 01:51:21,000
 In order to keep Andrew not so bored,

963
01:51:21,000 --> 01:51:29,000
 what do you think the position of Psalms in Augustine's own spirituality?

964
01:51:29,000 --> 01:51:35,000
 It's a big question, but anyway, I think you can have something to tell us about that.

965
01:51:35,000 --> 01:51:40,000
 Augustine said, "Psalms are the voice of Christ."

966
01:51:40,000 --> 01:51:42,000
 That was his saying.

967
01:51:42,000 --> 01:51:44,000
 And what about Psalms in the Orthodox tradition?

968
01:51:44,000 --> 01:51:49,000
 I often compare it to the role of the Koran in the Islamic piety,

969
01:51:49,000 --> 01:51:59,000
 because the Koran is compared to Psalms.

970
01:51:59,000 --> 01:52:05,000
 We have 150 Psalms, and the Koran has 114 parts.

971
01:52:05,000 --> 01:52:15,000
 And if you call it an Arabic psalm book, it would be easier to understand the structure.

972
01:52:15,000 --> 01:52:22,000
 And I think Orthodox liturgy and Orthodox piety recite Psalms.

973
01:52:22,000 --> 01:52:28,000
 It depends on language, because if you do it in English or in French, you have immediate understanding.

974
01:52:28,000 --> 01:52:34,000
 But in Russia, Ukraine, Belorussia, we do use Church Slavonic language,

975
01:52:34,000 --> 01:52:37,000
 which is not always understandable.

976
01:52:37,000 --> 01:52:44,000
 So we recite Psalms in a very, sometimes very anonymous way.

977
01:52:44,000 --> 01:52:49,000
 We just repeat, but some sayings are not understandable,

978
01:52:49,000 --> 01:52:55,000
 because of a lack of precision in translation at that time.

979
01:52:55,000 --> 01:53:06,000
 And that's why we need to also study it and to find the voice of Jesus Christ.

980
01:53:06,000 --> 01:53:08,000
 That's the Augustinian approach.

981
01:53:08,000 --> 01:53:14,000
 What is very interesting is that the Book of Psalms is,

982
01:53:14,000 --> 01:53:19,000
 I spoke about the Bible in the Orthodox everyday life,

983
01:53:19,000 --> 01:53:25,000
 and usually we don't, unfortunately, read the Bible as much as you do.

984
01:53:25,000 --> 01:53:34,000
 But Psalms, we read Psalms, and the whole Book of Psalms is repeated many times during Great Lent,

985
01:53:34,000 --> 01:53:38,000
 and also in ordinary time.

986
01:53:38,000 --> 01:53:43,000
 Many times you have from Psalm 1 to 150 during the week,

987
01:53:43,000 --> 01:53:48,000
 it's all Psalms read in our worship.

988
01:53:48,000 --> 01:53:51,000
 Very interesting, because it's a unique book,

989
01:53:51,000 --> 01:53:59,000
 which is very, very, quite, very often known by heart.

990
01:53:59,000 --> 01:54:05,000
 Maybe I was comparing that to the Koran, because many Orthodox say it by heart,

991
01:54:05,000 --> 01:54:08,000
 you know, like it comes automatically.

992
01:54:08,000 --> 01:54:18,000
 Even some calculation, I was in seminary, I went to a monastery to do some work with monks,

993
01:54:18,000 --> 01:54:27,000
 and they told me, "This work, you recite Psalm 50, and when you finish, it's done.

994
01:54:27,000 --> 01:54:34,000
 Go."

995
01:54:34,000 --> 01:54:40,000
 The Psalms, I think, are very important in Augustine.

996
01:54:40,000 --> 01:54:44,000
 His confessions, you can find the Psalms everywhere.

997
01:54:44,000 --> 01:54:50,000
 And the Psalms is about prayer to him, just like the confessions.

998
01:54:50,000 --> 01:54:56,000
 The confessions can be seen as extended, long prayer.

999
01:54:56,000 --> 01:55:02,000
 And I think he, in the confessions, after his return to the Church,

1000
01:55:02,000 --> 01:55:06,000
 return to his childhood faith, he went on retreat,

1001
01:55:06,000 --> 01:55:17,000
 and a session of the confessions actually took the form of a commentary of one of the Psalms.

1002
01:55:17,000 --> 01:55:26,000
 So I would say that he internalized the Psalms into his prayer and his life.

1003
01:55:26,000 --> 01:55:29,000
 Yeah, so I think he doesn't read the Psalms like us.

1004
01:55:29,000 --> 01:55:32,000
 He prays the Psalms.

1005
01:55:32,000 --> 01:55:38,000
 And John Calvin not only recites the Psalms, he sings the Psalms.

1006
01:55:38,000 --> 01:55:44,000
 So we are pretty in line together.

1007
01:55:44,000 --> 01:55:48,000
 Any questions?

1008
01:55:48,000 --> 01:55:51,000
 A sad one from you.

1009
01:55:51,000 --> 01:55:54,000
 I only ask one question each time, so I didn't break the rule.

1010
01:55:54,000 --> 01:56:00,000
 Anyway, you mentioned, I mean the discussion we mentioned about liturgy.

1011
01:56:00,000 --> 01:56:06,000
 Of course, in the Orthodox tradition, they emphasize liturgy is something that passed on from the past.

1012
01:56:06,000 --> 01:56:11,000
 So, you know, the Christendom liturgy is supposed to be from Christendom.

1013
01:56:11,000 --> 01:56:17,000
 Anyway, my question is that in the modern age, we talk about colloquial language,

1014
01:56:17,000 --> 01:56:22,000
 we talk about being engaged with the current culture,

1015
01:56:22,000 --> 01:56:31,000
 and obviously the Orthodox traditional liturgy is very out of touch with the modern culture in many ways.

1016
01:56:31,000 --> 01:56:36,000
 So in the Orthodox Church, the discussion about like,

1017
01:56:36,000 --> 01:56:41,000
 do we need to change some of the liturgies and some of the contemporary music

1018
01:56:41,000 --> 01:56:48,000
 instead of just reciting the Psalms in some, you know, reciting.

1019
01:56:48,000 --> 01:56:51,000
 Do we need some contemporary music in worship?

1020
01:56:51,000 --> 01:56:55,000
 Do they have this kind of discussion in the Orthodox community? I wonder.

1021
01:56:55,000 --> 01:57:01,000
 In such a degree, we do discuss about language,

1022
01:57:01,000 --> 01:57:08,000
 Church Slavonic, Russian, and different questions like this,

1023
01:57:08,000 --> 01:57:13,000
 but not changing completely our liturgy.

1024
01:57:13,000 --> 01:57:22,000
 For me personally, it was very astonishing that I discovered many meanings of our liturgy.

1025
01:57:22,000 --> 01:57:30,000
 I knew since many years as I started celebrating in French in Paris,

1026
01:57:30,000 --> 01:57:38,000
 as I served there, those translations were made by those intellectuals

1027
01:57:38,000 --> 01:57:45,000
 exposed by Lenin to France, and French was their mother tongue.

1028
01:57:45,000 --> 01:57:50,000
 And they were educated in philosophy and theology,

1029
01:57:50,000 --> 01:57:54,000
 and that's why they translated it in a magnificent way,

1030
01:57:54,000 --> 01:57:59,000
 very precisely, very good, very correct, very theological and profound.

1031
01:57:59,000 --> 01:58:04,000
 When I take a German translation of Orthodox liturgy,

1032
01:58:04,000 --> 01:58:08,000
 it's something I don't understand, even German people don't understand.

1033
01:58:08,000 --> 01:58:16,000
 We wanted to be the Calvinia, the Protestant pastor from Zurich,

1034
01:58:16,000 --> 01:58:25,000
 she's a pastor there, and we wanted to translate it together into a normal German language.

1035
01:58:25,000 --> 01:58:29,000
 You get the impression that people who translated it into German

1036
01:58:29,000 --> 01:58:34,000
 wanted to say, "We are not like you, we are different,

1037
01:58:34,000 --> 01:58:44,000
 we create another language to demonstrate what does it mean to be Orthodox among Germans."

1038
01:58:44,000 --> 01:58:49,000
 But they were Germans, you know, and the same story with Polish language.

1039
01:58:49,000 --> 01:58:54,000
 You know that the Polish Orthodox Church, it is very small, half a million people,

1040
01:58:54,000 --> 01:58:57,000
 but it's a very traditional church of Poland.

1041
01:58:57,000 --> 01:59:04,000
 We don't know about it, but it exists, and they do use Church Slavonic language.

1042
01:59:04,000 --> 01:59:12,000
 In some Polish translations, I try to celebrate in Polish language,

1043
01:59:12,000 --> 01:59:16,000
 but it's not Polish we use in our today's life,

1044
01:59:16,000 --> 01:59:23,000
 and it's very difficult, especially in questions of how to understand Orthodox liturgy.

1045
01:59:23,000 --> 01:59:28,000
 I wanted to show it to my Catholic friends, just what we pray,

1046
01:59:28,000 --> 01:59:32,000
 but the language was so strange that I felt ashamed.

1047
01:59:32,000 --> 01:59:36,000
 I think to respond to your question,

1048
01:59:36,000 --> 01:59:41,000
 no, we don't discuss about modern music in our liturgy, we separate both.

1049
01:59:41,000 --> 01:59:47,000
 If you want to pray with maybe young youth communities,

1050
01:59:47,000 --> 01:59:51,000
 you can sing something like Psalms, but not in the liturgy.

1051
01:59:51,000 --> 01:59:57,000
 Liturgy is more for us a classical way of doing things,

1052
01:59:57,000 --> 02:00:00,000
 but the question of language is very important.

1053
02:00:00,000 --> 02:00:07,000
 It seems to me we are really in the mood of exchange now,

1054
02:00:07,000 --> 02:00:12,000
 but our colleagues are a bit mindful of the time,

1055
02:00:12,000 --> 02:00:20,000
 so we really have a very rich exchange this evening.

